{"title_page": "Willie Nimmo", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Willie Nimmo\n| image       = \n| fullname    = William Brown Nimmo<ref>{{Hugman|14641|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=y|1934|01|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Forth, South Lanarkshire|Forth]], Scotland\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1991|08|17|1934|01|11|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Inveresk]], Scotland\n| position    = [[goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = Edinburgh Thistle\n| years1 = 1955\u20131956 | caps1 = 22  | goals1 = 0 | clubs1 = [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]\n| years2 = 1956\u20131957 | caps2 = 1   | goals2 = 0 | clubs2 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| years3 = 1957\u20131962 | caps3 = 182 | goals3 = 0 | clubs3 = [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]]\n| years4 = 1962\u20131963 | caps4 = 0   | goals4 = 0 | clubs4 = [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]]\n| totalcaps  = 205\n| totalgoals = 0\n }}\n'''Willie Nimmo''' (1934 \u2013 1991)<ref>{{NeilBrownPlayers|player5/willienimmo}}</ref> was a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]], who played for [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] in the [[Scottish Football League]], and [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] in the [[Football League]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nimmo, Willie}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Doncaster Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Willie Nimmo\n| image       = \n| fullname    = William Brown Nimmo<ref>{{Hugman|14641|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=y|1934|01|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Forth, South Lanarkshire|Forth]], Scotland\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1991|08|17|1934|01|11|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Inveresk]], Scotland\n| position    = [[goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = Edinburgh Thistle\n| years1 = 1955\u20131956 | caps1 = 22  | goals1 = 0 | clubs1 = [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]\n| years2 = 1956\u20131957 | caps2 = 1   | goals2 = 0 | clubs2 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| years3 = 1957\u20131962 | caps3 = 182 | goals3 = 0 | clubs3 = [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]]\n| years4 = 1962\u20131963 | caps4 = 0   | goals4 = 0 | clubs4 = [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]]\n| totalcaps  = 205\n| totalgoals = 0\n }}\n'''Willie Nimmo''' (1934 &ndash; 1991)<ref>{{NeilBrownPlayers|player5/willienimmo}}</ref> was a Scottish [[Association football|footballer]], who played for [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] in the [[Scottish Football League]], and [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] in the [[Football League]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nimmo, Willie}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Doncaster Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Mansfield Town F.C. players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willie_Nimmo"}
{"title_page": "Mary Carryl", "text_new": "{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Mary Carryl\n| image       = Portrait of Mrs. Mary Carol (4671349) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = Mrs. Mary Carryl\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place = Probably Ross, County Wexford\n| death_date  = November 22, 1809\n| death_place = [[Plas Newydd, Llangollen|Plas Newydd]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   = [[Plas Newydd, Llangollen|Plas Newydd]]\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    = [[Ladies of Llangollen]]\n| occupation  = servant, companion\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]\n}}\n'''Mary Carryl''' ( \u2013 November 22, 1809) was an Irish born loyal servant and friend of the celebrated [[Ladies of Llangollen]]. She served them up to her death and when the Ladies died they shared the same grave.\n\n==Life==\nCarryl was brought up in a poor family in [[Ross]] in County Wexford. Little is known about her until she is employed by Lady Elizabeth \"Betty\" and Sir William Fownes<ref name=rb/> at the [[Woodstock Estate]]. His grandfather had left William Fownes over 21,000 acres. William Fownes father, (also) Sir William Fownes, had been the [[List of mayors of Dublin|Mayor of Dublin]]. When her employer had married Elizabeth Ponsonby he had received \u00a34,000 as a dowry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/history-heritage/big-houses-of-ireland/the-tighe-family-woodstoc/|title=The Tighe Family & Woodstock Estate|website=www.askaboutireland.ie|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> With this money they built the six bayed three storey Woodstock House in County Kilkenny in 1745-7.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abandonedireland.com/Woodstock.html|title=Abandoned Ireland Woodstock House|website=www.abandonedireland.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Her employers had a child guest named Sarah Ponsonby who was Elizabeth's cousin. When Sarah's adult friend, Lady Eleanor Butler, ran away from home she was hidden in Sarah's room and Mary smuggled in food for her stowaway.<ref name=rb/>\n\nThe friendship between Lady Eleanor Butler and Sarah Ponsonby was not approved of by the Fownes or by Eleanor's guardians. When the friendship began Sarah was an unhappy thirteen year old orphan and she was captivated by the well educated Eleanor Butler. Butler was a 30 year old spinster who was no longer considered marriageable. Sarah was receiving unwanted attention from Sir William.<ref name=sarah>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-4182;jsessionid=29CE0CE1A611542438F1C044279BE827|title=Butler, Lady (Charlotte) Eleanor (1739\u20131829), elder of the two Ladies of Llangollen|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/4182|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> but eventually they agreed that they could leave Ireland together. They went to Llangollen in Wales where they set up home in a cottage called Plas Newydd. Meanwhile Mary, who was known as Mary the Bruiser had been fired after throwing a candlestick which wounded another servant. She was saved when Eleanor and Sarah sent for her to come to Llangollen.<ref name=rb/>\n[[File:Mary Carryl in St.Collen - servant to the Ladies of Llangollen.jpg|thumb|Mary Carryl's memorial is shared with the [[Ladies of Llangollen]] in the local church]]\nIn time Eleanor and Sarah would became notorious as \"The Ladies of Llangollen\", meanwhile Carryl became both their servant and the head of the household. She was loyal to her employers. She was said to have \"masculine qualities\" and Lady Eleanor's diary records how she would give as good as she got as she bargained loudly with the fishermen, the butchers and the inebriated.<ref name=rb>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48928;jsessionid=13F421B227FFC2E5BC169AF58C0CEBD8|title=Carryl, Mary (d. 1809), servant and friend of the Ladies of Llangollen|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48928|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe lifestyle of the [[Ladies of Llangollen]] attracted attention. They would receive notable visitors including the [[Duke of Wellington]]; the poets [[William Wordsworth]] and [[Anna Seward]], enlightenment leaders [[Erasmus Darwin]] and [[Josiah Wedgewood]] and writers including Sir [[Walter Scott]].<ref name=sarah/>\n\nCarryl died in [[Plas Newydd, Llangollen|Plas Newydd]] in 1809 and was buried in the churchyard of St. Collen\u2019s Church, Llangollen. She left a shilling to her brother and sister, but she left the field she owned to Sarah. In time the Ladies of Llangollen would die and they were buried beside their faithful servant.\n\nThe memorial monument to Mary Carryl, Eleanor Butler and Sarah Ponsonby in the churchyard of St. Collen's Church was erected in 1810. The inscription on Mary Carryl's part of the monument reads: In Memory of/ Mrs Mary Carryl/ Deceased 22 November 1809/ This monument is erected by Eleanor Butler,/ and Sarah Ponsonby, of Plasnewydd in this Parish./ Released from Earth and all its transient woes,/ She whose remains beneath this stone repose,/ Stedfast in Faith resigned her parting breath,/ Looked up with Christian joy, and smiled in Death!/ Patient, Industrious, Faithful, Generous, Kind,/ Her Conduct left the proudest far behind,/ Her Virtues dignified her humble birth,/ And raised her mind above this sordid earth,/ Attachment (Sacred bond of grateful breasts)/ Extinguished but with life, this Tomb attests,/ Reared by Two Friends who will her loss bemoan,/ 'Till with Her Ashes...Here shall rest, Their own.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carryl, Mary}}\n[[Category:1809 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kilkenny]]\n[[Category:Servants]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Mary Carryl\n| image       = Portrait of Mrs. Mary Carol (4671349) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = Mrs. Mary Carryl\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place = Probably Ross, County Wexford\n| death_date  = November 22, 1809\n| death_place = [[Plas Newydd]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   = [[Plas Newydd]]\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    = [[Ladies of Llangollen]]\n| occupation  = servant, companion\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]\n}}\n'''Mary Carryl''' ( \u2013 November 22, 1809) was an Irish born loyal servant and friend of the celebrated [[Ladies of Llangollen]]. She served them up to her death and when the Ladies died they shared the same grave.\n\n==Life==\nCarryl was brought up in a poor family in [[Ross]] in County Wexford. Little is known about her until she is employed by Lady Elizabeth \"Betty\" and Sir William Fownes<ref name=rb/> at the [[Woodstock Estate]]. His grandfather had left William Fownes over 21,000 acres. William Fownes father, (also) Sir William Fownes, had been the [[List of mayors of Dublin|Mayor of Dublin]]. When her employer had married Elizabeth Ponsonby he had received \u00a34,000 as a dowry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/history-heritage/big-houses-of-ireland/the-tighe-family-woodstoc/|title=The Tighe Family & Woodstock Estate|website=www.askaboutireland.ie|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> With this money they built the six bayed three storey Woodstock House in County Kilkenny in 1745-7.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abandonedireland.com/Woodstock.html|title=Abandoned Ireland Woodstock House|website=www.abandonedireland.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Her employers had a child guest named Sarah Ponsonby who was Elizabeth's cousin. When Sarah's adult friend, Lady Eleanor Butler, ran away from home she was hidden in Sarah's room and Mary smuggled in food for her stowaway.<ref name=rb/>\n\nThe friendship between Lady Eleanor Butler and Sarah Ponsonby was not approved of by the Fownes or by Eleanor's guardians. When the friendship began Sarah was an unhappy thirteen year old orphan and she was captivated by the well educated Eleanor Butler. Butler was a 30 year old spinster who was no longer considered marriageable. Sarah was receiving unwanted attention from Sir William.<ref name=sarah>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-4182;jsessionid=29CE0CE1A611542438F1C044279BE827|title=Butler, Lady (Charlotte) Eleanor (1739\u20131829), elder of the two Ladies of Llangollen|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/4182|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> but eventually they agreed that they could leave Ireland together. They went to Llangollen in Wales where they set up home in a cottage called Plas Newydd. Meanwhile Mary, who was known as Mary the Bruiser had been fired after throwing a candlestick which wounded another servant. She was saved when Eleanor and Sarah sent for her to come to Llangollen.<ref name=rb/>\n[[File:Mary Carryl in St.Collen - servant to the Ladies of Llangollen.jpg|thumb|Mary Carryl's memorial is shared with the [[Ladies of Llangollen]] in the local church]]\nIn time Eleanor and Sarah would became notorious as \"The Ladies of Llangollen\", meanwhile Carryl became both their servant and the head of the household. She was loyal to her employers. She was said to have \"masculine qualities\" and Lady Eleanor's diary records how she would give as good as she got as she bargained loudly with the fishermen, the butchers and the inebriated.<ref name=rb>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48928;jsessionid=13F421B227FFC2E5BC169AF58C0CEBD8|title=Carryl, Mary (d. 1809), servant and friend of the Ladies of Llangollen|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48928|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nThe lifestyle of the [[Ladies of Llangollen]] attracted attention. They would receive notable visitors including the [[Duke of Wellington]]; the poets [[William Wordsworth]] and [[Anna Seward]], enlightenment leaders [[Erasmus Darwin]] and [[Josiah Wedgewood]] and writers including Sir [[Walter Scott]].<ref name=sarah/>\n\nCarryl died in [[Plas Newydd]] in 1809 and was buried in the churchyard of St. Collen\u2019s Church, Llangollen. She left a shilling to her brother and sister, but she left the field she owned to Sarah. In time the Ladies of Llangollen would die and they were buried beside their faithful servant.\n\nThe memorial monument to Mary Carryl, Eleanor Butler and Sarah Ponsonby in the churchyard of St. Collen's Church was erected in 1810. The inscription on Mary Carryl's part of the monument reads: In Memory of/ Mrs Mary Carryl/ Deceased 22 November 1809/ This monument is erected by Eleanor Butler,/ and Sarah Ponsonby, of Plasnewydd in this Parish./ Released from Earth and all its transient woes,/ She whose remains beneath this stone repose,/ Stedfast in Faith resigned her parting breath,/ Looked up with Christian joy, and smiled in Death!/ Patient, Industrious, Faithful, Generous, Kind,/ Her Conduct left the proudest far behind,/ Her Virtues dignified her humble birth,/ And raised her mind above this sordid earth,/ Attachment (Sacred bond of grateful breasts)/ Extinguished but with life, this Tomb attests,/ Reared by Two Friends who will her loss bemoan,/ 'Till with Her Ashes...Here shall rest, Their own.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carryl, Mary}}\n[[Category:1809 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kilkenny]]\n[[Category:Servants]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toPlas Newydd(link changed toPlas Newydd, Llangollen; link changed toPlas Newydd, Llangollen; link changed toPlas Newydd, Llangollen) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia