4\n| years4      = 1990\u20131991 | clubs4 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]]                     | caps4 = 16  | goals4 = 1\n| years5      = 1991\u20131992 | clubs5 = [[Chorley F.C.|Chorley]]                     | caps5 =     | goals5 = \n| years6      = 1992\u20131993 | clubs6 = [[Bamber Bridge F.C.|Bamber Bridge]]         | caps6 =     | goals6 = \n| totalcaps   = 378\n| totalgoals  = 31\n}}\n'''William Balloch Stirling Naughton''' (born 20 March 1962) is a Scottish former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played in the [[English Football League|Football League]] as a [[winger (association football)|left winger]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player2/willienaughton.html |title=Willie Naughton |website=UK A\u2013Z Transfers |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naughton, Willie}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from East Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Walsall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Shrewsbury Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chorley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bamber Bridge F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willie_Naughton_(footballer,_born_1962)"}
{"title_page": "Strange Fruit", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|1939 song made famous by Billie Holiday}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Strange Fruit\n| cover      = Strange-Fruit-Commodore-1939.jpg\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Billie Holiday]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Fine and Mellow]]\n| released   = 1939\n| format     = 78 rpm\n| recorded   = April 20, 1939<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billieholidaysongs.com/all_songs.htm#1939 |title=Billie Holiday recording sessions |publisher=Billieholidaysongs.com |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528124535/http://www.billieholidaysongs.com/all_songs.htm#1939 |archivedate=May 28, 2010 }}</ref>\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Blues, jazz\n| length     = 3:02\n| label      = [[Commodore Records|Commodore]]\n| writer     = [[Abel Meeropol]]\n| producer   = [[Milt Gabler]]\n| prev_title = I'm Gonna Lock My Heart\n| prev_year  = 1938\n| next_title = [[God Bless the Child (Billie Holiday song)|God Bless the Child]]\n| next_year  = 1942\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Strange Fruit (Billie Holiday).ogg\n | description = \"Strange Fruit\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Strange Fruit'''\" is a song recorded by [[Billie Holiday]] in 1939, written by [[Abel Meeropol]] and published in 1937. It protested American racism, particularly the lynching of black Americans. Such lynchings had reached a peak in the Southern United States at the turn of the century, and the great majority of victims were black.<ref name=\"New York 1944 page 561\">[[Gunnar Myrdal]], An American Dilemma (New York, 1944), page 561.</ref> The song's lyrics are an extended metaphor linking a tree's fruit with lynching victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shmoop.com/strange-fruit/lyrics.html|title=Strange Fruit by Billie Holiday (lyrics)}}</ref> Meeropol set it to music with his wife and singer [[Laura Duncan (American Singer)|Laura Duncan]] and performed it as a protest song in [[New York City]] venues in the late 1930s, including [[Madison Square Garden]].\n\nThe song has been covered by numerous artists, including [[Nina Simone]], [[UB40]], [[Jeff Buckley]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Robert Wyatt]], and [[Dee Dee Bridgewater]], and Holiday's version was inducted into the [[List of Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients Q-Z|Grammy Hall of Fame]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.proquest.com/blog/pqblog/2015/PQIS2015-No-Encore-Billie-Holiday-Strange-Fruit.html|title=Hall of Fame|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> It was also included in the list of ''[[Songs of the Century]]'' by the Recording Industry of America and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]].<ref>\"[http://edition.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/03/07/list.top.365.songs/ Songs of the Century]\", ''CNN'', March 7, 2001.</ref> It has been called \"a declaration of war\" and \"the beginning of the civil rights movement\".<ref>\"[http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/first/m/margolick-fruit.html Review: Strange Fruit: Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an Early Cry for Civil Rights]\", ''The New York Times'', 2000.</ref>\n\n==Poem and song==\n[[Image:ThomasShippAbramSmith.jpg|thumb|Meeropol cited this photograph of the lynching of [[Thomas Shipp and Abram Smith]], August 7, 1930, as inspiring his poem.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129025516 |title=Strange Fruit: Anniversary Of A Lynching|publisher=NPR|date=August 6, 2010|accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>]]\n\n\"Strange Fruit\" originated as a poem written by Jewish-American writer, teacher and songwriter [[Abel Meeropol]], under his pseudonym Lewis Allan, as a protest against [[lynchings]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Margolick, David |title=Strange Fruit: Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an Early Cry for Civil Rights|url=https://archive.org/details/strangefruitbill00marg|url-access=registration |location=Philadelphia |publisher= Running Press |date=2000|pages= [https://archive.org/details/strangefruitbill00marg/page/25 25\u201327]}}</ref><ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite news|title=Strange Fruit is still a song for today |first= Edwin|last=Moore|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=September 18, 2010|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2010/sep/18/strange-fruit-song-today |accessdate=September 23, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=September 5, 2012|work=Morning Edition|publisher=NPR|title=The Strange Story of the Man Behind 'Strange Fruit' |author=Blair, Elizabeth (Host) |url=https://www.npr.org/2012/09/05/158933012/the-strange-story-of-the-man-behind-strange-fruit}}</ref> In the poem, Meeropol expressed his horror at lynchings, inspired by [[Lawrence Beitler]]'s photograph of the 1930 [[lynching of Thomas Shipp and Abram Smith]] in [[Marion, Indiana]].<ref name=\"Moore\"/> He published the poem under the title \"Bitter Fruit\" in 1937 in ''The New York Teacher'', a [[Trade union|union]] magazine of the [[Teachers Union]].<ref name=\"Lynskey\" /> Though Meeropol had asked others (notably [[Earl Robinson]]) to set his poems to music, he set \"Strange Fruit\" to music himself. His protest song gained a certain success in and around New York. Meeropol, his wife, and black vocalist Laura Duncan performed it at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 36\u201337.</ref>\n\nThe lyrics are under copyright but have been republished in full in an academic journal, with permission.<ref name=IJEpyright>{{cite journal|last=Meeropol|first=Abel|authorlink=Abel Meeropol |title=Strange fruit |journal=[[International Journal of Epidemiology]]|date=12 July 2006|volume=35|issue=4|page=902|doi=10.1093/ije/dyl173|url=http://ije.oxfordjournals.org/content/35/4/902.full.pdf+html |accessdate=January 6, 2013|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Billie Holiday's performances and recordings==\nOne version of events claims that [[Barney Josephson]], the founder of [[Caf\u00e9 Society]] in [[Greenwich Village]], New York's first [[Racial integration|integrated]] nightclub, heard the song and introduced it to [[Billie Holiday]]. Other reports say that Robert Gordon, who was directing Billie Holiday's show at Cafe Society, heard the song at Madison Square Garden and introduced it to her.<ref name=\"Lynskey\">{{cite news|last=Lynskey|first=Dorian|title=33 Revolutions Per Minute|publisher=Faber & Faber|location=London|year =2011|isbn=978-0-571-24134-7}}</ref> Holiday first performed the song at Caf\u00e9 Society in 1939. She said that singing it made her fearful of retaliation but, because its imagery reminded her of her father, she continued to sing the piece, making it a regular part of her live performances.<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 40\u201346.</ref> Because of the power of the song, Josephson drew up some rules: Holiday would close with it; the waiters would stop all service in advance; the room would be in darkness except for a spotlight on Holiday's face; and there would be no encore.<ref name=\"Lynskey\"/> During the musical introduction to the song, Holiday stood with her eyes closed, as if she were evoking a prayer.\n\nHoliday approached her recording label, Columbia, about the song, but the company feared reaction by record retailers in [[Southern United States|the South]], as well as negative reaction from affiliates of its co-owned radio network, [[CBS]].<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 61\u201362.</ref> When Holiday's producer [[John H. Hammond|John Hammond]] also refused to record it, she turned to her friend [[Milt Gabler]], whose [[Commodore Records|Commodore]] label produced alternative jazz.<ref>{{cite AV media||people=[[Billy Crystal]]|date=2004|title=[[700 Sundays (film)|700 Sundays]] |publisher=HBO |id={{imdb title|tt3383040 |title=700 Sundays}}|oclc=112}}</ref> Holiday sang \"Strange Fruit\" for him ''a cappella'', and moved him to tears. Columbia gave Holiday a one-session release from her contract so she could record it; [[Frankie Newton]]'s eight-piece Cafe Society Band was used for the session. Because Gabler worried the song was too short, he asked pianist [[Sonny White]] to improvise an introduction. On the recording, Holiday starts singing after 70 seconds.<ref name=\"Lynskey\"/> It was recorded on April 20, 1939.<ref>Aida Amoako, \"[http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20190415-strange-fruit-the-most-shocking-song-of-all-time Strange Fruit: The most shocking song of all time?]\", ''Songs that made history'', [[BBC]]. April 17, 2019.</ref> Gabler worked out a special arrangement with [[Vocalion Records]] to record and distribute the song.<ref>Billy Crystal, ''700 Sundays'', pp. 46\u201347.</ref>\n\nHoliday recorded two major sessions of the song at Commodore, one in 1939 and one in 1944. The song was highly regarded; the 1939 recording eventually sold a million copies,<ref name=\"Moore\"/> in time becoming Holiday's biggest-selling recording.\n\nIn her autobiography, ''[[Lady Sings the Blues (book)|Lady Sings the Blues]]'', Holiday suggested that she, together with Meeropol, her accompanist Sonny White, and arranger Danny Mendelsohn, set the poem to music. The writers [[David Margolick]] and [[Hilton Als]] dismissed that claim in their work ''Strange Fruit: The Biography of a Song'', writing that hers was \"an account that may set a record for most misinformation per column inch\". When challenged, Holiday\u2014whose autobiography had been [[ghostwriter|ghostwritten]] by [[William Dufty]]\u2014claimed, \"I ain't never read that book.\"<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 31\u201332.</ref>\n\nBillie Holiday was so well known for her rendition of \"Strange Fruit\" that \"she crafted a relationship to the song that would make them inseparable\".<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Perry |first=Samuel |year=2012 |title=\"Strange Fruit,\" Ekphrasis, and the Lynching Scene |journal=Rhetoric Society Quarterly|volume=43:5|issue=5|pages=449\u2013474|doi=10.1080/02773945.2013.839822}}</ref> Holiday's 1939 version of the song was included in the [[National Recording Registry]] on January 27, 2003.\n\nIn October 1939, Samuel Grafton of the ''[[New York Post]]'' said of \"Strange Fruit\", \"If the anger of the exploited ever mounts high enough in the South, it now has its [[La Marseillaise|Marseillaise]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/feb/16/protest-songs-billie-holiday-strange-fruit|title=Strange Fruit: the first great protest song|first=Dorian|last=Lynskey|work=The Guardian |date=February 15, 2011}}</ref> In an attempt to have a two-thirds majority in the Senate that would break the filibusters by the southern senators, anti-racism activists were encouraged to mail copies of \"Strange Fruit\" to their senators.<ref name=\"Margolick\">{{cite book|last1=Margolick|first1=David|title=Strange fruit : Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an early cry for civil rights |date=2000 |publisher=Running Press |isbn=0762406771|page=77}}</ref>\n\n==Notable covers==\nNotable cover versions of this song include [[Nina Simone]] (whose version was sampled in [[Kanye West]]'s \"[[Blood on the Leaves]]\"<ref name=\"lara\">{{cite web |first=Lara |last=Pellegrinelli |title=Evolution Of A Song: 'Strange Fruit' |publisher=npr.org|url=https://www.npr.org/2009/06/22/105699329/evolution-of-a-song-strange-fruit|date=22 June 2009 |accessdate=23 February 2015 }}</ref>), [[Ren\u00e9 Marie]],<ref name=lara /> [[Jeff Buckley]],<ref name=lara /> [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]],<ref name=times /> [[Dee Dee Bridgewater]],<ref name=times /> [[Josh White]],<ref name=loc.gov>{{cite web|first=loc|last=gov|title=Josh White:Strange Fruit|publisher=loc.gov|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/smor.ALB-1521/|accessdate=13 May 2019 }}</ref> and [[UB40]].<ref name=times>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/strangefruitbill00marg|url-status=dead|title=Strange Fruit, Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an Early Cry for Civil Rights|author=Margolick, David |publisher=NYTimes |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-7624-0677-7|accessdate=10 September 2017|url-access=registration }}</ref> Nina Simone recorded the song in 1965,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20190415-strange-fruit-the-most-shocking-song-of-all-time |date=17 April 2019 |author=Aida Amoako |work=BBC |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> a recording described by journalist [[DAVID MARGOLICK]] in the New York Times as featuring a \"plain and unsentimental voice\".<ref name=lara /> Journalist Lara Pellegrinelli wrote that Jeff Buckley while singing it \"seems to meditate on the meaning of humanity the way [[Walt Whitman]] did, considering all of its glorious and horrifying possibilities\".<ref name=lara /> Rene Marie's rendition was coupled with Confederate anthem \"[[Dixie (song)|Dixie]]\", making for an \"uncomfortable juxtaposition\", according to Pellegrinelli.<ref name=lara /> ''[[LA Times]]'' noted that Siouxsie and the Banshees's version contained \"a solemn string section behind the vocals\" and \"a bridge of New Orleans funeral-march jazz\" which enhanced the singer's \"evocative interpretation\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Terry|last=Atkinson|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-03-15-ca-10501-story.html|title=Siouxsie Looks Back|newspaper=L.A. Times|date=15 March 1987|accessdate=15 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711171722/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-03-15-ca-10501-story.html|archive-date=2019-07-11 }}</ref> The group's rendition was selected by the ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo magazine]]'' staff to be included on the compilation ''Music Is Love: 15 Tracks That Changed The World ''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Music-Is-Love-15-Tracks-That-Changed-The-World/release/988921|title=Music Is Love! (15 Tracks That Changed The World) CD|magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|date=June 2007|accessdate=10 September 2017}} Siouxsie and the Banshes's rendition from their 1987 ''[[Through the Looking Glass (Siouxsie & the Banshees album)|Through the Looking Glass]]'' album was selected to feature on this compilation</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=John Edward |last=Hasse |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/strange-fruit-still-haunting-at-80-11556654252|title='Strange Fruit': Still Haunting at 80|publisher=Walt Street Journal|date=30 April 2019 |accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 1999: ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named \"Strange Fruit\" as \"Best Song of the Century\" in its issue dated December 31, 1999.<ref>Billy Crystal, ''700 Sundays'', p. 47.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McNally|first=Owen|date=March 30, 2000|title='Song of the century' chilling: Graphic lyrics of 'the first unmuted cry against racism' are making a comeback|url=|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]] }}</ref>\n* 2002: The [[Library of Congress]] honored the song as one of 50 recordings chosen that year to add to the [[National Recording Registry]].<ref>{{cite web|title=National Recording Registry 2002 |url=https://www.loc.gov/loc/lcib/0401/nrr-02.html|website=loc.gov|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 2010: The ''[[New Statesman]]'' listed it as one of the \"Top 20 Political Songs\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/music/2010/03/strange-fruit-holiday-blood|title=Top 20 Political Songs: Strange Fruit|first=Ian K|last=Smith|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=March 25, 2010|accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref>\n* ''2011: [[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' listed the song as Number One on \"100 Songs of the South\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/ajc/swf/songsofthesouth/index.html |title=100 Songs of the South &#124; accessAtlanta.com|publisher=Alt.coxnewsweb.com|date=|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Fiction==\n* [[Lillian Smith (author)|Lillian Smith]]'s novel ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' (1944) was said to have been inspired by Holiday's version of the song.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bass, Erin Z.|url=http://deepsouthmag.com/2012/12/the-strange-life-of-strange-fruit/|title=The Strange Life of Strange Fruit|work=Deep South Magazine|date= December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last1=Clarke|first1=Donald|date=1995|title=Billie Holiday: Wishing on the Moon|location=M\u00fcnchen|publisher=Piper|isbn=978-3-492-03756-3}}\n* {{cite book|authorlink=Angela Yvonne Davis|last=Davis|first=Angela|date=1999|title=Blues Legacies and Black Feminism|publisher=Vintage Books|isbn=978-0-679-77126-5}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Holiday|first1=Billie|last2=Dufty|first2=William|date=1992|title=Lady Sings the Blues|publisher=Edition Nautilus|isbn=978-3-89401-110-9}} Autobiography.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/strangefruit/ \"Strange Fruit\"], ''Independent Lens'', PBS\n* [http://newsreel.org/video/STRANGE-FRUIT ''Strange Fruit''], Newsreel documentary\n* [http://www.shmoop.com/strange-fruit/ \"Strange Fruit\"], Shmoop, analysis of lyrics, historical and literary allusions - student & teaching guide\n* {{MetroLyrics song|billie-holiday|strange-fruit}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{MusicBrainz work|mbid=e14b0233-5d5e-3d46-9ff5-87f89bb0ffb4|name=Strange Fruit}}\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03jb1w1 BBC Radio 4 - ''Soul Music'', Series 17, Strange Fruit]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25034438 \"Strange Fruit: A protest song with enduring relevance\"]\n*{{cite podcast\n| url= http://www.radiodiaries.org/podcast-strange-fruit-voices-from-a-lynching/\n| title=Strange Fruit\n| website=Radio Diaries\n| publisher=PRX\n| access-date=2015-09-04\n}}\n\n{{Billie Holiday}}\n{{Lynching in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:1939 songs]]\n[[Category:Billie Holiday songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about trees]]\n[[Category:Lynching in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:Songs against racism and xenophobia]]\n[[Category:Songs based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Songs based on poems]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in American magazines]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|1939 song made famous by Billie Holiday}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Strange Fruit\n| cover      = Strange-Fruit-Commodore-1939.jpg\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Billie Holiday]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Fine and Mellow]]\n| released   = 1939\n| format     = 78 rpm\n| recorded   = April 20, 1939<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billieholidaysongs.com/all_songs.htm#1939 |title=Billie Holiday recording sessions |publisher=Billieholidaysongs.com |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528124535/http://www.billieholidaysongs.com/all_songs.htm#1939 |archivedate=May 28, 2010 }}</ref>\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Blues, jazz\n| length     = 3:02\n| label      = [[Commodore Records|Commodore]]\n| writer     = [[Abel Meeropol]]\n| producer   = [[Milt Gabler]]\n| prev_title = I'm Gonna Lock My Heart\n| prev_year  = 1938\n| next_title = [[God Bless the Child (Billie Holiday song)|God Bless the Child]]\n| next_year  = 1942\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Strange Fruit (Billie Holiday).ogg\n | description = \"Strange Fruit\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Strange Fruit'''\" is a song recorded by [[Billie Holiday]] in 1939, written by [[Abel Meeropol]] and published in 1937. It protested American racism, particularly the lynching of black Americans. Such lynchings had reached a peak in the Southern United States at the turn of the century, and the great majority of victims were black.<ref name=\"New York 1944 page 561\">[[Gunnar Myrdal]], An American Dilemma (New York, 1944), page 561.</ref> The song's lyrics are an extended metaphor linking a tree's fruit with lynching victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shmoop.com/strange-fruit/lyrics.html|title=Strange Fruit by Billie Holiday (lyrics)}}</ref> Meeropol set it to music with his wife and singer [[Laura Duncan (American Singer)|Laura Duncan]] and performed it as a protest song in [[New York City]] venues in the late 1930s, including [[Madison Square Garden]].\n\nThe song has been covered by numerous artists, including [[Nina Simone]], [[UB40]], [[Jeff Buckley]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Robert Wyatt]], and [[Dee Dee Bridgewater]], and Holiday's version was inducted into the [[List of Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients Q-Z|Grammy Hall of Fame]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.proquest.com/blog/pqblog/2015/PQIS2015-No-Encore-Billie-Holiday-Strange-Fruit.html|title=Hall of Fame|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> It was also included in the list of ''[[Songs of the Century]]'' by the Recording Industry of America and the [[National Endowment for the Arts]].<ref>\"[http://edition.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/03/07/list.top.365.songs/ Songs of the Century]\", ''CNN'', March 7, 2001.</ref> It has been called \"a declaration of war\" and \"the beginning of the civil rights movement\".<ref>\"[http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/first/m/margolick-fruit.html Review: Strange Fruit: Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an Early Cry for Civil Rights]\", ''The New York Times'', 2000.</ref>\n\n==Poem and song==\n[[Image:ThomasShippAbramSmith.jpg|thumb|Meeropol cited this photograph of the lynching of [[Thomas Shipp and Abram Smith]], August 7, 1930, as inspiring his poem.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129025516 |title=Strange Fruit: Anniversary Of A Lynching|publisher=NPR|date=August 6, 2010|accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>]]\n\n\"Strange Fruit\" originated as a poem written by Jewish-American writer, teacher and songwriter [[Abel Meeropol]], under his pseudonym Lewis Allan, as a protest against [[lynchings]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Margolick, David |title=Strange Fruit: Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an Early Cry for Civil Rights|url=https://archive.org/details/strangefruitbill00marg|url-access=registration |location=Philadelphia |publisher= Running Press |date=2000|pages= [https://archive.org/details/strangefruitbill00marg/page/25 25\u201327]}}</ref><ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite news|title=Strange Fruit is still a song for today |first= Edwin|last=Moore|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=September 18, 2010|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2010/sep/18/strange-fruit-song-today |accessdate=September 23, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=September 5, 2012|work=Morning Edition|publisher=NPR|title=The Strange Story of the Man Behind 'Strange Fruit' |author=Blair, Elizabeth (Host) |url=https://www.npr.org/2012/09/05/158933012/the-strange-story-of-the-man-behind-strange-fruit}}</ref> In the poem, Meeropol expressed his horror at lynchings, inspired by [[Lawrence Beitler]]'s photograph of the 1930 [[lynching of Thomas Shipp and Abram Smith]] in [[Marion, Indiana]].<ref name=\"Moore\"/> He published the poem under the title \"Bitter Fruit\" in 1937 in ''The New York Teacher'', a [[Trade union|union]] magazine of the [[Teachers Union]].<ref name=\"Lynskey\" /> Though Meeropol had asked others (notably [[Earl Robinson]]) to set his poems to music, he set \"Strange Fruit\" to music himself. His protest song gained a certain success in and around New York. Meeropol, his wife, and black vocalist Laura Duncan performed it at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 36\u201337.</ref>\n\nThe lyrics are under copyright but have been republished in full in an academic journal, with permission.<ref name=IJEpyright>{{cite journal|last=Meeropol|first=Abel|authorlink=Abel Meeropol |title=Strange fruit |journal=[[International Journal of Epidemiology]]|date=12 July 2006|volume=35|issue=4|page=902|doi=10.1093/ije/dyl173|url=http://ije.oxfordjournals.org/content/35/4/902.full.pdf+html |accessdate=January 6, 2013|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Billie Holiday's performances and recordings==\nOne version of events claims that [[Barney Josephson]], the founder of [[Caf\u00e9 Society]] in [[Greenwich Village]], New York's first [[Racial integration|integrated]] nightclub, heard the song and introduced it to [[Billie Holiday]]. Other reports say that Robert Gordon, who was directing Billie Holiday's show at Cafe Society, heard the song at Madison Square Garden and introduced it to her.<ref name=\"Lynskey\">{{cite news|last=Lynskey|first=Dorian|title=33 Revolutions Per Minute|publisher=Faber & Faber|location=London|year =2011|isbn=978-0-571-24134-7}}</ref> Holiday first performed the song at Caf\u00e9 Society in 1939. She said that singing it made her fearful of retaliation but, because its imagery reminded her of her father, she continued to sing the piece, making it a regular part of her live performances.<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 40\u201346.</ref> Because of the power of the song, Josephson drew up some rules: Holiday would close with it; the waiters would stop all service in advance; the room would be in darkness except for a spotlight on Holiday's face; and there would be no encore.<ref name=\"Lynskey\"/> During the musical introduction to the song, Holiday stood with her eyes closed, as if she were evoking a prayer.\n\nHoliday approached her recording label, Columbia, about the song, but the company feared reaction by record retailers in [[Southern United States|the South]], as well as negative reaction from affiliates of its co-owned radio network, [[CBS]].<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 61\u201362.</ref> When Holiday's producer [[John H. Hammond|John Hammond]] also refused to record it, she turned to her friend [[Milt Gabler]], whose [[Commodore Records|Commodore]] label produced alternative jazz.<ref>{{cite AV media||people=[[Billy Crystal]]|date=2004|title=[[700 Sundays (film)|700 Sundays]] |publisher=HBO |id={{imdb title|tt3383040 |title=700 Sundays}}|oclc=112}}</ref> Holiday sang \"Strange Fruit\" for him ''a cappella'', and moved him to tears. Columbia gave Holiday a one-session release from her contract so she could record it; [[Frankie Newton]]'s eight-piece Cafe Society Band was used for the session. Because Gabler worried the song was too short, he asked pianist [[Sonny White]] to improvise an introduction. On the recording, Holiday starts singing after 70 seconds.<ref name=\"Lynskey\"/> It was recorded on April 20, 1939.<ref>Aida Amoako, \"[http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20190415-strange-fruit-the-most-shocking-song-of-all-time Strange Fruit: The most shocking song of all time?]\", ''Songs that made history'', [[BBC]]. April 17, 2019.</ref> Gabler worked out a special arrangement with [[Vocalion Records]] to record and distribute the song.<ref>Billy Crystal, ''700 Sundays'', pp. 46\u201347.</ref>\n\nHoliday recorded two major sessions of the song at Commodore, one in 1939 and one in 1944. The song was highly regarded; the 1939 recording eventually sold a million copies,<ref name=\"Moore\"/> in time becoming Holiday's biggest-selling recording.\n\nIn her autobiography, ''[[Lady Sings the Blues (book)|Lady Sings the Blues]]'', Holiday suggested that she, together with Meeropol, her accompanist Sonny White, and arranger Danny Mendelsohn, set the poem to music. The writers [[David Margolick]] and [[Hilton Als]] dismissed that claim in their work ''Strange Fruit: The Biography of a Song'', writing that hers was \"an account that may set a record for most misinformation per column inch\". When challenged, Holiday\u2014whose autobiography had been [[ghostwriter|ghostwritten]] by [[William Dufty]]\u2014claimed, \"I ain't never read that book.\"<ref>Margolick, ''Strange Fruit'', pp. 31\u201332.</ref>\n\nBillie Holiday was so well known for her rendition of \"Strange Fruit\" that \"she crafted a relationship to the song that would make them inseparable\".<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Perry |first=Samuel |year=2012 |title=\"Strange Fruit,\" Ekphrasis, and the Lynching Scene |journal=Rhetoric Society Quarterly|volume=43:5|issue=5|pages=449\u2013474|doi=10.1080/02773945.2013.839822}}</ref> Holiday's 1939 version of the song was included in the [[National Recording Registry]] on January 27, 2003.\n\nIn October 1939, Samuel Grafton of the ''[[New York Post]]'' said of \"Strange Fruit\", \"If the anger of the exploited ever mounts high enough in the South, it now has its [[La Marseillaise|Marseillaise]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/feb/16/protest-songs-billie-holiday-strange-fruit|title=Strange Fruit: the first great protest song|first=Dorian|last=Lynskey|work=The Guardian |date=February 15, 2011}}</ref> In an attempt to have a two-thirds majority in the Senate that would break the filibusters by the southern senators, anti-racism activists were encouraged to mail copies of \"Strange Fruit\" to their senators.<ref name=\"Margolick\">{{cite book|last1=Margolick|first1=David|title=Strange fruit : Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an early cry for civil rights |date=2000 |publisher=Running Press |isbn=0762406771|page=77}}</ref>\n\n==Notable covers==\nNotable cover versions of this song include [[Nina Simone]] (whose version was sampled in [[Kanye West]]'s \"[[Blood on the Leaves]]\"<ref name=\"lara\">{{cite web |first=Lara |last=Pellegrinelli |title=Evolution Of A Song: 'Strange Fruit' |publisher=npr.org|url=https://www.npr.org/2009/06/22/105699329/evolution-of-a-song-strange-fruit|date=22 June 2009 |accessdate=23 February 2015 }}</ref>), [[Ren\u00e9 Marie]],<ref name=lara /> [[Jeff Buckley]],<ref name=lara /> [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]],<ref name=times /> [[Dee Dee Bridgewater]],<ref name=times /> [[Josh White]],<ref name=loc.gov>{{cite web|first=loc|last=gov|title=Josh White:Strange Fruit|publisher=loc.gov|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/smor.ALB-1521/|accessdate=13 May 2019 }}</ref> and [[UB40]].<ref name=times>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/strangefruitbill00marg|url-status=dead|title=Strange Fruit, Billie Holiday, Caf\u00e9 Society, and an Early Cry for Civil Rights|author=Margolick, David |publisher=NYTimes |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-7624-0677-7|accessdate=10 September 2017|url-access=registration }}</ref> Nina Simone dramatized \"Strange Fruit\" in the context of the Civil Rights Movement with a plain and unsentimental voice.<ref name=lara /> Journalist Lara Pellegrinelli wrote that Jeff Buckley while singing it \"seems to meditate on the meaning of humanity the way [[Walt Whitman]] did, considering all of its glorious and horrifying possibilities\".<ref name=lara /> Rene Marie's rendition was coupled with Confederate anthem \"[[Dixie (song)|Dixie]]\", making for an \"uncomfortable juxtaposition\", according to Pellegrinelli.<ref name=lara /> ''[[LA Times]]'' noted that Siouxsie and the Banshees's version contained \"a solemn string section behind the vocals\" and \"a bridge of New Orleans funeral-march jazz\" which enhanced the singer's \"evocative interpretation\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Terry|last=Atkinson|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-03-15-ca-10501-story.html|title=Siouxsie Looks Back|newspaper=L.A. Times|date=15 March 1987|accessdate=15 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711171722/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-03-15-ca-10501-story.html|archive-date=2019-07-11 }}</ref> The group's rendition was selected by the ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo magazine]]'' staff to be included on the compilation ''Music Is Love: 15 Tracks That Changed The World ''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Music-Is-Love-15-Tracks-That-Changed-The-World/release/988921|title=Music Is Love! (15 Tracks That Changed The World) CD|magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|date=June 2007|accessdate=10 September 2017}} Siouxsie and the Banshes's rendition from their 1987 ''[[Through the Looking Glass (Siouxsie & the Banshees album)|Through the Looking Glass]]'' album was selected to feature on this compilation</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=John Edward |last=Hasse |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/strange-fruit-still-haunting-at-80-11556654252|title='Strange Fruit': Still Haunting at 80|publisher=Walt Street Journal|date=30 April 2019 |accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 1999: ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named \"Strange Fruit\" as \"Best Song of the Century\" in its issue dated December 31, 1999.<ref>Billy Crystal, ''700 Sundays'', p. 47.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McNally|first=Owen|date=March 30, 2000|title='Song of the century' chilling: Graphic lyrics of 'the first unmuted cry against racism' are making a comeback|url=|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]] }}</ref>\n* 2002: The [[Library of Congress]] honored the song as one of 50 recordings chosen that year to add to the [[National Recording Registry]].<ref>{{cite web|title=National Recording Registry 2002 |url=https://www.loc.gov/loc/lcib/0401/nrr-02.html|website=loc.gov|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 2010: The ''[[New Statesman]]'' listed it as one of the \"Top 20 Political Songs\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/music/2010/03/strange-fruit-holiday-blood|title=Top 20 Political Songs: Strange Fruit|first=Ian K|last=Smith|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=March 25, 2010|accessdate=March 25, 2010}}</ref>\n* ''2011: [[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' listed the song as Number One on \"100 Songs of the South\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/ajc/swf/songsofthesouth/index.html |title=100 Songs of the South &#124; accessAtlanta.com|publisher=Alt.coxnewsweb.com|date=|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Fiction==\n* [[Lillian Smith (author)|Lillian Smith]]'s novel ''[[Strange Fruit (novel)|Strange Fruit]]'' (1944) was said to have been inspired by Holiday's version of the song.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bass, Erin Z.|url=http://deepsouthmag.com/2012/12/the-strange-life-of-strange-fruit/|title=The Strange Life of Strange Fruit|work=Deep South Magazine|date= December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last1=Clarke|first1=Donald|date=1995|title=Billie Holiday: Wishing on the Moon|location=M\u00fcnchen|publisher=Piper|isbn=978-3-492-03756-3}}\n* {{cite book|authorlink=Angela Yvonne Davis|last=Davis|first=Angela|date=1999|title=Blues Legacies and Black Feminism|publisher=Vintage Books|isbn=978-0-679-77126-5}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Holiday|first1=Billie|last2=Dufty|first2=William|date=1992|title=Lady Sings the Blues|publisher=Edition Nautilus|isbn=978-3-89401-110-9}} Autobiography.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/strangefruit/ \"Strange Fruit\"], ''Independent Lens'', PBS\n* [http://newsreel.org/video/STRANGE-FRUIT ''Strange Fruit''], Newsreel documentary\n* [http://www.shmoop.com/strange-fruit/ \"Strange Fruit\"], Shmoop, analysis of lyrics, historical and literary allusions - student & teaching guide\n* {{MetroLyrics song|billie-holiday|strange-fruit}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{MusicBrainz work|mbid=e14b0233-5d5e-3d46-9ff5-87f89bb0ffb4|name=Strange Fruit}}\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03jb1w1 BBC Radio 4 - ''Soul Music'', Series 17, Strange Fruit]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25034438 \"Strange Fruit: A protest song with enduring relevance\"]\n*{{cite podcast\n| url= http://www.radiodiaries.org/podcast-strange-fruit-voices-from-a-lynching/\n| title=Strange Fruit\n| website=Radio Diaries\n| publisher=PRX\n| access-date=2015-09-04\n}}\n\n{{Billie Holiday}}\n{{Lynching in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:1939 songs]]\n[[Category:Billie Holiday songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about trees]]\n[[Category:Lynching in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:Songs against racism and xenophobia]]\n[[Category:Songs based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Songs based on poems]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in American magazines]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n", "name_user": "Amakuru", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable covers:c/e copyvio line", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strange_Fruit"}
{"title_page": "Willie Naughton", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Willie Naughton (footballer born 1962)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Willie Naughton\n| fullname       = William A. Naughton\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1870|7|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Garnkirk]], Scotland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1906|4|23|1870|7|16|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Bothwell]], Lanarkshire, Scotland\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Outside-right]]\n| years1         = 1887\u20131889| clubs1   = Carfin Shamrock                   | caps1  =     | goals1  =\n| years2         = 1888     | clubs2   = \u2192 [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] (loan)    | caps2  =     | goals2  =\n| years3         = 1889     | clubs3   = \u2192 Uddingston  (loan)                     | caps3  =     | goals3  =\n| years4         = 1889     | clubs4   = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]            | caps4  =     | goals4  =\n| years5         = 1889     | clubs5   = Carfin Shamrock                   | caps5  =     | goals5  =\n| years6         = 1889\u20131890| clubs6   = [[Glasgow Hibernian F.C.|Glasgow Hibernian]]                | caps6  =     | goals6  =\n| years7         = 1890     | clubs7   = [[Wishaw F.C.|Wishaw Thistle]]    | caps7  =     | goals7  =\n| years8         = 1890\u20131895| clubs8   = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]         | caps8  = 91  | goals8  = 24\n| years9         = 1895\u20131898| clubs9   = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]  | caps9  = 36  | goals9  = 15\n| years10        = 1898     | clubs10  = Carfin Rovers                     | caps10 =     | goals10 =\n| totalcaps = 127 | totalgoals = 39\n}}\n\n'''William A. Naughton''' (16 July 1870 \u2013 23 April 1906)<ref name = FATS>{{cite book|last1=Chalk|first1=Gary|last2=Holley|first2=Duncan|last3=Bull|first3=David|title=All the Saints: A Complete Players' Who's Who of Southampton FC|year=2013|location=Southampton|publisher=Hagiology Publishing|isbn=978-0-9926-8640-6|p=186}}</ref> was a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]], who played as an [[outside-forward]] for various clubs in Scotland and England in the 1880s and 1890s, including [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]] and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]. Throughout his career he was known as \"Chippy\".<ref name = \"ABC\">{{cite book | title=The Alphabet of the Saints|last= Holley |first= Duncan |author2=Chalk, Gary | publisher= ACL & Polar Publishing | year=1992| isbn=0-9514862-3-3|page=252}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |last=Joyce |first=Michael |year=2004 |publisher=Tony Brown |location=Nottingham |isbn=1-899468-67-6|page=194 }}</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nNaughton was born in [[Garnkirk]], north-east of [[Glasgow]] and in his teenage years played for a variety of clubs across Scotland, including [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in Edinburgh and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in Glasgow.\n\nIn July 1890, he moved to England to join [[Stoke F.C.|Stoke]] of [[the Football League]], for whom he made over one hundred appearances, generally at [[inside-right]].<ref>Matthews, Tony: \"The Encyclopedia of Stoke City \" (Lion Press, 1994, {{ISBN|1-85983-100-1}})</ref> In 1891, he was suspended for receiving payments from his club while registered as an amateur.<ref name = \"ABC\"/>\n\nOn 26 April 1893, he was part of the Stoke team which visited the [[County Ground, Southampton|County Ground]] to play a friendly match against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton St Mary's]]. Even with the future founder of football in Brazil, [[Charles William Miller|Charles Miller]]<ref name=\"Different\">{{cite book |last= Hamilton |first= Aidan | title= An Entirely Different Game, The British Influence on Brazilian Football |year= 1998 |publisher= Mainstream Publishing |isbn= 1-84018-041-2}}</ref> playing at [[outside-left]], the \"Saints\" were \"''outplayed fairly and squarely on every point''\",<ref name = \"MOM\"/> losing 8\u20130. Despite the result, it was reported that the spectators \"''thoroughly enjoyed the exhibition''\" and looked forward to witnessing \"''more matches of a similar character''\" in future.<ref name = \"MOM\">{{cite book | title=Match of the Millennium|last= Bull |first= David |author2=Brunskell, Bob  | publisher=Hagiology Publishing | year=2000| isbn=0-9534474-1-3|pages=12\u201313}}</ref> Also playing for Stoke were [[Charles Baker (footballer)|Charles Baker]], [[Lachie Thomson]] and [[Alf Littlehales]], all of whom were to move to Southampton within two years.\n\nNaughton moved to [[Southern England|the south coast]] in April 1895 to join Southampton, prior to the start of their [[Southern Football League 1895-96|second season]] in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]]. Naughton made his debut at [[inside-right]] for the opening match of the season, a 1\u20130 defeat at champions [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], retaining his place for the remainder of the season, missing only one league match.<ref>{{cite book | title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|last= Chalk|first= Gary|author2=Holley, Duncan  | publisher= Breedon Books| year=1987| isbn= 0-907969-22-4 |pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\nNaughton missed the first three matches of [[Southern Football League 1896-97|the 1896\u201397 season]], returning on 24 October at [[outside-right]]. On 7 November, he scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in an 8\u20133 victory over [[New Brompton F.C.|New Brompton]]. He continued at outside-right for the rest of the season, scoring a total of six league goals.<ref name = \"Chalk20\">{{cite book | title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|last=  |first= | publisher= | isbn= |pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Described as an \"''inveterate practical joker''\",<ref name = \"ABC\"/> Naughton's elusive wing play and pin-point centres to forwards [[Jack Farrell (footballer)|Jack Farrell]] and [[Robert Buchanan (footballer)|Bob Buchanan]], helped the \"Saints\" to claim the Southern League title for the first of six occasions over the next eight years.\n\nIn the [[1896\u201397 FA Cup|FA Cup]], Naughton played in every match until the Saints reached the Second Round proper, where they met [[Manchester United F.C.|Newton Heath]]. The first match, at the [[County Ground, Southampton|County Ground]] on 13 February 1897 ended 1\u20131. As a result of an injury, Naughton was unavailable for the replay four days later, when he was replaced by [[James Spellacy]], making his only [[first-team]] appearance for the Saints. Naughton was badly missed and Newton Heath ran out 3\u20131 winners.<ref name = \"Chalk20\"/>\n\nFor [[Southern Football League 1897-98|the next season]], Southampton signed [[Jimmy Yates]] who replaced Naughton at [[outside-left]]. Naughton only made three further appearances before returning to Scotland at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite book | title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|last=  |first= | publisher= | isbn= |pages=22\u201323}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nNaughton played local football in Scotland until about 1899. In 1904, he was declared \"of no fixed abode\" and was admitted to [[Kirklands Asylum]] in [[Bothwell]], where he died on 23 April 1906, aged 35.<ref name = FATS/>\n\n==Career statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Test Match\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]\n|[[1890\u201391 Stoke F.C. season|1890\u201391]]\n|[[Football Alliance]]\n|6||2||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||2\n|-\n|[[1891\u201392 Stoke F.C. season|1891\u201392]]\n|[[The Football League|Football League]]\n|16||3||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||18||3\n|-\n|[[1892\u201393 Stoke F.C. season|1892\u201393]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|24||6||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||6\n|-\n|[[1893\u201394 Stoke F.C. season|1893\u201394]]\n|First Division\n|28||10||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||29||10\n|-\n|[[1894\u201395 Stoke F.C. season|1894\u201395]]\n|First Division\n|17||3||0||0||1||0||18||3\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!91!!24!!4!!0!!1!!0!!96!!24\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n|[[1895\u201396 Southampton St. Mary's F.C. season|1895\u201396]]\n|[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]\n|17||8||4||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||21||11\n|-\n|[[1896\u201397 Southampton St. Mary's F.C. season|1896\u201397]]\n|Southern League\n|16||6||6||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||6\n|-\n|[[1897\u201398 Southampton F.C. season|1897\u201398]]\n|Southern League\n|3||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!36!!15!!11!!3!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||47!!18\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!127!!39!!15!!3!!1!!0!!143!!42\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Stoke'''\n*[[Football Alliance]] champions: [[1890\u201391 Football Alliance|1890\u201391]]\n\n'''Southampton'''\n*[[Southern Football League|Southern League]] champions: [[Southern Football League 1896-97|1896\u201397]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naughton, Willie}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from North Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hibernian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League players]]\n[[Category:Football Alliance players]]\n[[Category:Association football outside forwards]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Willie Naughton (footballer born 1962)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Willie Naughton\n| fullname       = William A. Naughton\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1870|7|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Garnkirk]], Scotland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1906|4|23|1870|7|16|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Bothwell]], Lanarkshire, Scotland\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)|Outside-right]]\n| years1         = 1887\u20131889| clubs1   = Carfin Shamrock                   | caps1  =     | goals1  =\n| years2         = 1888     | clubs2   = \u2192 [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] (loan)    | caps2  =     | goals2  =\n| years3         = 1889     | clubs3   = \u2192 Uddingston  (loan)                     | caps3  =     | goals3  =\n| years4         = 1889     | clubs4   = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]            | caps4  =     | goals4  =\n| years5         = 1889     | clubs5   = Carfin Shamrock                   | caps5  =     | goals5  =\n| years6         = 1889\u20131890| clubs6   = [[Glasgow Hibernian F.C.|Glasgow Hibernian]]                | caps6  =     | goals6  =\n| years7         = 1890     | clubs7   = [[Wishaw F.C.|Wishaw Thistle]]    | caps7  =     | goals7  =\n| years8         = 1890\u20131895| clubs8   = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]         | caps8  = 91  | goals8  = 24\n| years9         = 1895\u20131898| clubs9   = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]  | caps9  = 36  | goals9  = 15\n| years10        = 1898     | clubs10  = Carfin Rovers                     | caps10 =     | goals10 =\n| totalcaps = 127 | totalgoals = 39\n}}\n\n'''William A. Naughton''' (16 July 1870 \u2013 23 April 1906)<ref name = FATS>{{cite book|last1=Chalk|first1=Gary|last2=Holley|first2=Duncan|last3=Bull|first3=David|title=All the Saints: A Complete Players' Who's Who of Southampton FC|year=2013|location=Southampton|publisher=Hagiology Publishing|isbn=978-0-9926-8640-6|p=186}}</ref> was a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]], who played as an [[outside-forward]] for various clubs in Scotland and England in the 1880s and 1890s, including [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]] and [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]. Throughout his career he was known as \"Chippy\".<ref name = \"ABC\">{{cite book | title=The Alphabet of the Saints|last= Holley |first= Duncan |author2=Chalk, Gary | publisher= ACL & Polar Publishing | year=1992| isbn=0-9514862-3-3|page=252}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |last=Joyce |first=Michael |year=2004 |publisher=Tony Brown |location=Nottingham |isbn=1-899468-67-6|page=194 }}</ref>\n\n==Football career==\nNaughton was born in [[Garnkirk]], north-east of [[Glasgow]] and in his teenage years played for a variety of clubs across Scotland, including [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] in Edinburgh and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in Glasgow.\n\nIn July 1890, he moved to England to join [[Stoke F.C.|Stoke]] of [[the Football League]], for whom he made over one hundred appearances, generally at [[inside-right]].<ref>Matthews, Tony: \"The Encyclopedia of Stoke City \" (Lion Press, 1994, {{ISBN|1-85983-100-1}})</ref> In 1891, he was suspended for receiving payments from his club while registered as an amateur.<ref name = \"ABC\"/>\n\nOn 26 April 1893, he was part of the Stoke team which visited the [[County Ground, Southampton|County Ground]] to play a friendly match against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton St Mary's]]. Even with the future founder of football in [[Brazil]], [[Charles William Miller|Charles Miller]]<ref name=\"Different\">{{cite book |last= Hamilton |first= Aidan | title= An Entirely Different Game, The British Influence on Brazilian Football |year= 1998 |publisher= Mainstream Publishing |isbn= 1-84018-041-2}}</ref> playing at [[outside-left]], the \"Saints\" were \"''outplayed fairly and squarely on every point''\",<ref name = \"MOM\"/> losing 8\u20130. Despite the result, it was reported that the spectators \"''thoroughly enjoyed the exhibition''\" and looked forward to witnessing \"''more matches of a similar character''\" in future.<ref name = \"MOM\">{{cite book | title=Match of the Millennium|last= Bull |first= David |author2=Brunskell, Bob  | publisher=Hagiology Publishing | year=2000| isbn=0-9534474-1-3|pages=12\u201313}}</ref> Also playing for Stoke were [[Charles Baker (footballer)|Charles Baker]], [[Lachie Thomson]] and [[Alf Littlehales]], all of whom were to move to Southampton within two years.\n\nNaughton moved to [[Southern England|the south coast]] in April 1895 to join Southampton, prior to the start of their [[Southern Football League 1895-96|second season]] in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]]. Naughton made his debut at [[inside-right]] for the opening match of the season, a 1\u20130 defeat at champions [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], retaining his place for the remainder of the season, missing only one league match.<ref>{{cite book | title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|last= Chalk|first= Gary|author2=Holley, Duncan  | publisher= Breedon Books| year=1987| isbn= 0-907969-22-4 |pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\nNaughton missed the first three matches of [[Southern Football League 1896-97|the 1896\u201397 season]], returning on 24 October at [[outside-right]]. On 7 November, he scored a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in an 8\u20133 victory over [[New Brompton F.C.|New Brompton]]. He continued at outside-right for the rest of the season, scoring a total of six league goals.<ref name = \"Chalk20\">{{cite book | title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|last=  |first= | publisher= | isbn= |pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Described as an \"''inveterate practical joker''\",<ref name = \"ABC\"/> Naughton's elusive wing play and pin-point centres to forwards [[Jack Farrell (footballer)|Jack Farrell]] and [[Robert Buchanan (footballer)|Bob Buchanan]], helped the \"Saints\" to claim the Southern League title for the first of six occasions over the next eight years.\n\nIn the [[1896\u201397 FA Cup|FA Cup]], Naughton played in every match until the Saints reached the Second Round proper, where they met [[Manchester United F.C.|Newton Heath]]. The first match, at the [[County Ground, Southampton|County Ground]] on 13 February 1897 ended 1\u20131. As a result of an injury, Naughton was unavailable for the replay four days later, when he was replaced by [[James Spellacy]], making his only [[first-team]] appearance for the Saints. Naughton was badly missed and Newton Heath ran out 3\u20131 winners.<ref name = \"Chalk20\"/>\n\nFor [[Southern Football League 1897-98|the next season]], Southampton signed [[Jimmy Yates]] who replaced Naughton at [[outside-left]]. Naughton only made three further appearances before returning to Scotland at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite book | title=Saints \u2013 A complete record|last=  |first= | publisher= | isbn= |pages=22\u201323}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nNaughton played local football in Scotland until about 1899. In 1904, he was declared \"of no fixed abode\" and was admitted to [[Kirklands Asylum]] in [[Bothwell]], where he died on 23 April 1906, aged 35.<ref name = FATS/>\n\n==Career statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Test Match\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]]\n|[[1890\u201391 Stoke F.C. season|1890\u201391]]\n|[[Football Alliance]]\n|6||2||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||2\n|-\n|[[1891\u201392 Stoke F.C. season|1891\u201392]]\n|[[The Football League|Football League]]\n|16||3||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||18||3\n|-\n|[[1892\u201393 Stoke F.C. season|1892\u201393]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|24||6||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||6\n|-\n|[[1893\u201394 Stoke F.C. season|1893\u201394]]\n|First Division\n|28||10||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||29||10\n|-\n|[[1894\u201395 Stoke F.C. season|1894\u201395]]\n|First Division\n|17||3||0||0||1||0||18||3\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!91!!24!!4!!0!!1!!0!!96!!24\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n|[[1895\u201396 Southampton St. Mary's F.C. season|1895\u201396]]\n|[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]\n|17||8||4||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||21||11\n|-\n|[[1896\u201397 Southampton St. Mary's F.C. season|1896\u201397]]\n|Southern League\n|16||6||6||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||6\n|-\n|[[1897\u201398 Southampton F.C. season|1897\u201398]]\n|Southern League\n|3||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!36!!15!!11!!3!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||47!!18\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!127!!39!!15!!3!!1!!0!!143!!42\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Stoke'''\n*[[Football Alliance]] champions: [[1890\u201391 Football Alliance|1890\u201391]]\n\n'''Southampton'''\n*[[Southern Football League|Southern League]] champions: [[Southern Football League 1896-97|1896\u201397]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naughton, Willie}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from North Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hibernian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League players]]\n[[Category:Football Alliance players]]\n[[Category:Association football outside forwards]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFootball career:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willie_Naughton"}
{"title_page": "Lois Wheeler Snow", "text_new": "'''Lois Wheeler Snow''' (July 12, 1920 \u2013 April 3, 2018) was an American actress who became known for her criticism of abuse of human rights.\n\n==Early years==\nThe daughter of Raymond Joseph Wheeler and Katherine Kurtz Wheeler, Snow was born '''Lois Wheeler''' on July 12, 1920 in [[Stockton, California]].<ref name=\"NYT-obit\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/obituaries/lois-wheeler-snow-dies.html |title=Lois Wheeler Snow, Critic of Human Rights Abuses in China, Dies at 97 |last=Qin |first=Amy |date=2018-04-11 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180415032204/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/obituaries/lois-wheeler-snow-dies.html |archive-date=15 April 2018 |access-date=2019-03-06 |url-status=live }}</ref> Her father was Stockton's mayor, and her mother was a homemaker. She remained in Stockton to study drama at the [[College of the Pacific (University of the Pacific)|College of the Pacific]].<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> While there, she acted with the college's Little Theater troupe<ref>{{cite news |title='Our Town' to Be Presented |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26366906/oakland_tribune/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=September 17, 1939 |location=California, Oakland |page=22|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and was \"a principal ingenue\" for two years.<ref>{{cite news |title='Romeo and Juliet' Next for College of Pacific Thespians With 50 Students in Cast |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26367889/oakland_tribune/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=January 26, 1941 |location=California, Oakland |page=27|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> She also won the F. Melvyn Lawson Award as the person who \"contributed the most to the Little Theater season.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Soanes |first1=Wood |title=Critics Differ as to Merits of 'Innocent Voyage,' Setting for Broadway Debut of Stockton Girl |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26368099/oakland_tribune/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=December 19, 1943 |location=California, Oakland |page=24|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Her performance in a college play led to her receiving a scholarship to study at the [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre]] in New York City\u2014much to her parents' disappointment.<ref name=\"bg\">{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Marjory |title=Lois Wheeler's Role in 'Dear Ruth' Won Without Misrepresenting Her Age |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26365930/lois_wheeler/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=The Boston Globe |date=September 22, 1946 |location=Massachusetts, Boston |page=24 A|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> She was also one of the [[Actors Studio|Actors Studio's]] founding members.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\n==Acting==\nSnow used her acting talent to obtain her first professional role. Although she had graduated from college, she removed her makeup, wore clothing typical of a teenager, and convinced officials at the [[Theatre Guild]] that she was a 15-year-old girl from out of town who wanted to act. The result was the desired role in ''The Innocent Voyage'' (1943).<ref name=\"bg\" /> Her other Broadway credits include ''The Fifth Season'' (1953), ''Dinosaur Wharf'' (1951), ''The Young and Fair'' (1948), ''[[All My Sons]]'' (1947), ''Trio'' (1944), and ''Pick-up Girl'' (1944).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lois Wheeler |url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/lois-wheeler-64668 |website=Internet Broadway Database |publisher=The Broadway League |accessdate=19 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219025311/https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/lois-wheeler-64668 |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref> She acted in the touring company of ''[[Dear Ruth]]'' as well as in its Broadway production.<ref>{{cite news |title=County Residents Have Share in New Play |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26367718/the_journal_news/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=The Journal News |date=January 30, 1958 |location=New York, White Plains |page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared on film in ''My Foolish Heart'' (1949). On television, she portrayed nurse Janet Jackson on ''[[Guiding Light|The Guiding Light]]'' from 1954 to 1958.<ref name=\"r\">{{cite news |last1=Fitzgerald |first1=Michael |title=Fitzgerald: The woman who knew Chairman Mao |url=https://www.recordnet.com/news/20180414/fitzgerald-woman-who-knew-chairman-mao |accessdate=19 December 2018 |work=Recordnet.com |date=April 14, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219033336/https://www.recordnet.com/news/20180414/fitzgerald-woman-who-knew-chairman-mao |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with China==\nIn 2011, Snow began an essay with the statement, \"China became part of my life when I met and married Edgar Snow.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Snow |first1=Lois |title=Let the Devil Take the Hindmost |url=http://www.chinafile.com/let-devil-take-hindmost |website=ChinaFile |publisher=Center on U.S.-China Relations at Asia Society |accessdate=19 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419132745/http://www.chinafile.com/let-devil-take-hindmost |archivedate=19 April 2018}}</ref> She first visited China in 1970 with her husband. The couple received a welcome fit for royalty, appearing publicly with Chairman Mao and meeting First Premier Zhou.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> That meeting was seen by some people as \"a back-channel invitation to President Richard Nixon to visit.\"<ref name=r/> Mao and Zhou later sent a medical team to the Snows' home in Switzerland after Edgar Snow's health failed. Following his death, she frequently visited China and stayed friendly with the country's leaders.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\nA turning point in the Snow-China relationship occurred after the [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests]]. Snow told a reporter that the Communist Party's treatment of protesters \"just woke me up.\"<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> She said that she would never return to the country, and she attempted to leverage her late husband's status in China as she wrote to leaders about the effects of their policies on families.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> After Snow found out that money she had sent to families of victims of oppression had been confiscated, she broke her vow.<ref name=\"t\">{{cite news |last1=Turner |first1=Mia |title='Tiananmen Just Woke Me Up' |url=http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/features/interviews/int.snow.html |accessdate=19 December 2018 |work=TIME asia |date=2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219035303/http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/features/interviews/int.snow.html |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref> In 2000 she went with her son to China, finding a reception much different from her earlier experience. Surveillance followed them, and a group of police officers prevented them from meeting with an activist whose son had been killed during the protests in Tiananmen.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\n== Blacklisting ==\nAllegations of Communist leanings after they were questioned by the FBI<ref name=r/> led to the Snows' being [[Blacklisting#Hollywood anti-communist blacklist|blacklisted]] and unable to obtain work in the United States. In 1959, they moved to Switzerland, settling in the [[Lake Geneva]] region.<ref>{{cite news |title=China critic Lois Wheeler Snow dies in Swiss home |url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/broadway-actress_china-critic-lois-wheeler-snow-dies-in-swiss-home/44041706 |accessdate=19 December 2018 |work=SWI swissinfo.ch |publisher=Swiss Broadcasting Corporation |date=April 12, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219032258/https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/broadway-actress_china-critic-lois-wheeler-snow-dies-in-swiss-home/44041706 |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married writer Edgar Snow in May 1949 in Sneeden's Landing, New York.<ref>{{cite news |title=Actress Lois Wheeler Wed to Author Snow |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26367535/lois_wheeler_edgar_snow/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=The Miami News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 3, 1949 |location=Florida, Miami |page=6|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn April 3, 2018, Snow died at a hospital in [[Nyon|Nyon, Switzerland]], at age 97.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Biography|California|Film|Television|Theater}} \n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snow, Lois Wheeler}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n", "text_old": "'''Lois Wheeler Snow''' (July 12, 1920 \u2013 April 3, 2018) was an American actress who became known for her criticism of abuse of human rights.\n\n==Early years==\nThe daughter of Raymond Joseph Wheeler and Katherine Kurtz Wheeler, Snow was born '''Lois Wheeler''' on July 12, 1920 in [[Stockton, California]].<ref name=\"NYT-obit\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/obituaries/lois-wheeler-snow-dies.html |title=Lois Wheeler Snow, Critic of Human Rights Abuses in China, Dies at 97 |last=Qin |first=Amy |date=2018-04-11 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180415032204/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/11/obituaries/lois-wheeler-snow-dies.html |archive-date=15 April 2018 |access-date=2019-03-06 |url-status=live }}</ref> Her father was Stockton's mayor, and her mother was a homemaker. She remained in Stockton to study drama at the [[College of the Pacific (University of the Pacific)|College of the Pacific]].<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> While there, she acted with the college's Little Theater troupe<ref>{{cite news |title='Our Town' to Be Presented |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26366906/oakland_tribune/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=September 17, 1939 |location=California, Oakland |page=22|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> and was \"a principal ingenue\" for two years.<ref>{{cite news |title='Romeo and Juliet' Next for College of Pacific Thespians With 50 Students in Cast |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26367889/oakland_tribune/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=January 26, 1941 |location=California, Oakland |page=27|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> She also won the F. Melvyn Lawson Award as the person who \"contributed the most to the Little Theater season.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Soanes |first1=Wood |title=Critics Differ as to Merits of 'Innocent Voyage,' Setting for Broadway Debut of Stockton Girl |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26368099/oakland_tribune/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=Oakland Tribune |date=December 19, 1943 |location=California, Oakland |page=24|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Her performance in a college play led to her receiving a scholarship to study at the [[Neighborhood Playhouse School of the Theatre]] in New York City\u2014much to her parents' disappointment.<ref name=\"bg\">{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Marjory |title=Lois Wheeler's Role in 'Dear Ruth' Won Without Misrepresenting Her Age |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26365930/lois_wheeler/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=The Boston Globe |date=September 22, 1946 |location=Massachusetts, Boston |page=24 A|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> She was also one of the [[Actors Studio|Actors Studio's]] founding members.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\n==Acting==\nSnow used her acting talent to obtain her first professional role. Although she had graduated from college, she removed her makeup, wore clothing typical of a teenager, and convinced officials at the [[Theatre Guild]] that she was a 15-year-old girl from out of town who wanted to act. The result was the desired role in ''The Innocent Voyage'' (1943).<ref name=\"bg\" /> Her other Broadway credits include ''The Fifth Season'' (1953), ''Dinosaur Wharf'' (1951), ''The Young and Fair'' (1948), ''[[All My Sons]]'' (1947), ''Trio'' (1944), and ''Pick-up Girl'' (1944).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lois Wheeler |url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/lois-wheeler-64668 |website=Internet Broadway Database |publisher=The Broadway League |accessdate=19 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219025311/https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/lois-wheeler-64668 |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref> She acted in the touring company of ''[[Dear Ruth]]'' as well as in its Broadway production.<ref>{{cite news |title=County Residents Have Share in New Play |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26367718/the_journal_news/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=The Journal News |date=January 30, 1958 |location=New York, White Plains |page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared on film in ''My Foolish Heart'' (1949). On television, she portrayed nurse Janet Jackson on ''[[Guiding Light|The Guiding Light]]'' from 1954 to 1958.<ref name=\"r\">{{cite news |last1=Fitzgerald |first1=Michael |title=Fitzgerald: The woman who knew Chairman Mao |url=https://www.recordnet.com/news/20180414/fitzgerald-woman-who-knew-chairman-mao |accessdate=19 December 2018 |work=Recordnet.com |date=April 14, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219033336/https://www.recordnet.com/news/20180414/fitzgerald-woman-who-knew-chairman-mao |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Relations with China==\nIn 2011, Snow began an essay with the statement, \"China became part of my life when I met and married Edgar Snow.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Snow |first1=Lois |title=Let the Devil Take the Hindmost |url=http://www.chinafile.com/let-devil-take-hindmost |website=ChinaFile |publisher=Center on U.S.-China Relations at Asia Society |accessdate=19 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419132745/http://www.chinafile.com/let-devil-take-hindmost |archivedate=19 April 2018}}</ref> She first visited China in 1970 with her husband. The couple received a welcome fit for royalty, appearing publicly with Chairman Mao and meeting First Premier Zhou.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> That meeting was seen by some people as \"a back-channel invitation to President Richard Nixon to visit.\"<ref name=r/> Mao and Zhou later sent a medical team to the Snows' home in Switzerland after Edgar Snow's health failed. Following his death, she frequently visited China and stayed friendly with the country's leaders.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\nA turning point in the Snow-China relationship occurred after the [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests]]. Snow told a reporter that the Communist Party's treatment of protesters \"just woke me up.\"<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> She said that she would never return to the country, and she attempted to leverage her late husband's status in China as she wrote to leaders about the effects of their policies on families.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" /> After Snow found out that money she had sent to families of victims of oppression had been confiscated, she broke her vow.<ref name=\"t\">{{cite news |last1=Turner |first1=Mia |title='Tiananmen Just Woke Me Up' |url=http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/features/interviews/int.snow.html |accessdate=19 December 2018 |work=TIME asia |date=2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219035303/http://edition.cnn.com/ASIANOW/time/features/interviews/int.snow.html |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref> In 2000 she went with her son to China, finding a reception much different from her earlier experience. Surveillance followed them, and a group of police officers prevented them from meeting with an activist whose son had been killed during the protests in Tiananmen.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\n== Blacklisting ==\nAllegations of Communist leanings after they were questioned by the FBI<ref name=r/> led to the Snows' being [[Blacklisting#Hollywood anti-communist blacklist|blacklisted]] and unable to obtain work in the United States. In 1959, they moved to Switzerland, settling in the [[Lake Geneva]] region.<ref>{{cite news |title=China critic Lois Wheeler Snow dies in Swiss home |url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/broadway-actress_china-critic-lois-wheeler-snow-dies-in-swiss-home/44041706 |accessdate=19 December 2018 |work=SWI swissinfo.ch |publisher=Swiss Broadcasting Corporation |date=April 12, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219032258/https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/broadway-actress_china-critic-lois-wheeler-snow-dies-in-swiss-home/44041706 |archivedate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married writer Edgar Snow in May 1949 in Sneeden's Landing, New York.<ref>{{cite news |title=Actress Lois Wheeler Wed to Author Snow |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26367535/lois_wheeler_edgar_snow/ |accessdate=20 December 2018 |work=The Miami News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 3, 1949 |location=Florida, Miami |page=6|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn April 3, 2018, Snow died at a hospital in [[Nyon|Nyon, Switzerland]], at age 97.<ref name=\"NYT-obit\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|Biography|California|Film|Television|Theater}} \n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snow, Lois Wheeler}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lois_Wheeler_Snow"}
{"title_page": "List of the oldest buildings in Massachusetts", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{See also|List of the oldest buildings in the United States}}\nThis article attempts to list the oldest buildings in the Commonwealth of [[Massachusetts]] in the United States of America, including the oldest houses in Massachusetts and any other surviving structures. Some dates are approximate (indicated with a \"circa\" or \"c.\") and based on architectural studies and historical records, while other dates are based on [[dendrochronology]]. All entries should include citation with reference to: 17th century architectural features; a report by an architectural historian; or dendrochronology.  Sites on the list are generally from the [[First Period]] of American architecture. Only [[First Period]] houses built prior to 1700 are suitable for inclusion on this list or the building must be the oldest of its type.\n\nThe [[Fairbanks House (Dedham, Massachusetts)|Fairbanks House]] (built 1637-1641) is the oldest house verified using dendrochronology, followed by the [[James Blake House]] (built in 1661), but most First Period structures in Massachusetts have not yet been tested with dendrochronology surveys. The town of [[Ipswich, Massachusetts]] is believed to have approximately 60 First Period houses, purportedly more than any other town in America.<ref>Images and histories of First Period houses in Ipswich are at the [https://historicipswich.org/first-period-houses/ Historic Ipswich website].</ref>\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Building\n! Image\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Notes\n|-\n|  [[Williams-Barker House]]\n| [[File:Williams-Barker House in Scituate Massachusetts MA Barker Tavern.png|100px]]\n| [[Scituate, Massachusetts]]\n| 1634 c.\n| Core of house is believed to date from 1634, but is now extensively renovated<ref>https://www.plymouthdeeds.org/sites/plymouthcr/files/u60/williams-barker_house.pdf</ref><ref>''Old Scituate'' (1921), p. 84</ref> and currently operated as a tavern.<ref>https://www.barkertavern.com/</ref> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|  Austin Crombie House\n| [[File:Austin Crombie House 85 Summer Street Manchester by the Sea Massachusetts MA USA built circa 1635.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Manchester, Massachusetts]]\n| 1635 c.<ref>https://historicipswich.org/first-period-houses-of-essex-county/</ref>\n| House is believed to date from 1635 and is located at 85 Summer Street.<ref>https://www.manchester.ma.us/DocumentCenter/View/2745/Appendix-III-Historic-Properties-Eligibility-Criteria-Documents</ref><ref>http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=MAN.22</ref> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|  [[Fairbanks House (Dedham, Massachusetts)|Fairbanks House]]\n| [[Image:Fairbanks house dedham.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Dedham, Massachusetts]]\n| 1637-1641\n| Oldest verified wood-frame house in America, timbers dated from 1637-1641 using [[dendrochronology]], and the oldest house verified with dendrochronology in Massachusetts; largely preserved in original state.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qhyxeOAKW5kC&pg=PA218&dq=fairbanks+house+oldest Elsie Lathrop  \"Historic Houses of Early America\" (Kessinger, New York: 2006) pg. 218 (accessed on Google Book Search)]</ref><ref>Oxford Dendrochronology Survery https://www.dendrochronology.com/fhd-1.html</ref>\n|-\n|  Thomas Bourne House\t\n| [[File:Thomas Bourne House at 1308 Ocean Street in Marshfield MA Massachusetts built circa 1639.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshfield, Massachusetts]]\n| 1639 c.\n| Located at 1308 Ocean Street;<ref>Marshfield House Survey https://www.marshfield-ma.gov/historical-commission/pages/house-survey</ref> House is believed to date from 1639.<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\">https://firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com/houses/</ref> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|[[Richard Sparrow House]]\n|[[File:Richard Sparrow House in Plymouth Massachusetts.jpg|alt=Richard Sparrow House|100px]]\n|[[Plymouth, Massachusetts]]\n|1640 c.\n|The Richard Sparrow House is a historic house and museum at 42 Summer Street in Plymouth, Massachusetts and the allegedly the oldest surviving house in Plymouth. No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|  [[Samuel Lucius-Thomas Howland House]]\t\n| [[File:Old_Houses_at_Foot_of_North_Street,_Plymouth,_Mass_(NYPL_b12647398-79386).tiff|100px]]\n| [[Plymouth, Massachusetts]]\n| 1640 c.\n| Located at 36 North Street near [[Plymouth Rock]]; House is believed to date from 1640.<ref>William Thomas Davis, ''Ancient Landmarks of Plymouth: Part I. Historical Sketch and Titles of Estates. Part II. Genealogical Register of Plymouth Families, Volumes 1-2'' (A. Williams, 1887), 177-178</ref><ref>Donna DeFabio Curtin, ''Plymouth'' (2011), p. 46</ref><ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|  Joseph Andrews-Perez Lincoln House\n| [[File:Perez Lincoln house.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Hingham, Massachusetts|Hingham]], now in [[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]]\n| 1640 c.\n| House is believed to date from 1640 and was moved from Hingham to Chatham.<ref>\"17th-century house moved to new home,\" Jul 14, 2013, ''The Boston Globe'' https://www.bostonglobe.com \u203a regionals \u203a south \u203a 2013/07/13 \u203a</ref><ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|  Capt. Thomas Willett House-Upland Meadows\t\n| [[File:Historic American Buildings Survey Arthur C. Haskell, Photographer Oct. 16, 1937 (c) EXT- FRONT and SIDE, LOOKING NORTHEAST - Captain Thomas Willett House, Kingston, Plymouth HABS MASS,12-KING,4-3.tif|100px]]\n| [[Kingston, Massachusetts]]\n| 1640 c.\n| Located at 27 Wapping Road; The back ell of the house is believed to date from 1640.<ref>Massachusetts Historical Commission  http://kplma.org/hh/hh63.pdf</ref><ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n| [[Wing Fort House]]\n| [[File:Wing Fort House exterior.jpg|100px]]\n| [[East Sandwich, Massachusetts]]\n| 1641<ref name=\"wing\">{{cite web|title=Wing Fort House|url=http://www.wingfamily.org/wingfamilyforthouse.html|website=Wing Family of America|publisher=Wing Family of America, Inc|accessdate=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n| The oldest home in New England continuously owned by the same family; now a museum.<ref name=\"wing\" /> Dendrochronological dating was attempted in 2007, but was unsuccessful due to \"many of the samples having too many narrow rings, some having too few rings, and to the lack of reference chronologies from the south-eastern part of Massachusetts.\"<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\">http://www.oxford-dendrolab.com/massachusetts.asp</ref>\n|-\n|Edmond Hawes-Barker Hunt House\t\n|[[File:Edmond Hawes-Barker Hunt House aka Edwin Hunt House 8 Hounds Ditch Lane in Duxbury MA Massachusetts built circa 1641.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Duxbury, Massachusetts]]\t\n| 1641 c.\n| aka as the Edwin Hunt House at 8 Hounds Ditch Lane; House is believed to date from 1641.<ref>LOCATING 17TH CENTURY HOMESITES IN DUXBURY: A preliminary Assessment Prepared by Craig S. Chartier, Plymouth Archaeological Rediscovery Project, for The Duxbury Rural and Historical Society</ref><ref>\"The Hount House 1641\" Thursday August 29, 1968, Duxbury Clipper, https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5b16b2389772aeb3c1acfbc1/t/5c658bd77817f7b5b388e15a/1550158807829/Hunt%2C+Edmond+1641_1968.08.pdf</ref><ref>https://sites.rootsweb.com/~huntpage/edmund0001.htm</ref> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|John Doane House\t\t\n|[[File:John Doane House at 34 Wapping Road Kingston MA Massachusetts built circa 1644.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Kingston, Massachusetts]]\t\n| 1644 c.\n| Located at 34 Wapping Road;<ref>http://kplma.org/om/items/show/1864</ref> House is believed to date from 1644.<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n|[[Nathaniel Felton Houses|Nathaniel Felton Sr. House]]\t\t\n|[[File:PeabodyMA_NathanielFeltonSrHouse.jpg|100px]]\n| [[