\"/>\n| 803 Main Street<ref>https://historicipswich.org/2017/02/05/colonial-houses-of-west-newbury-ma/</ref>\n|-\n|  [[Dillingham House]]\t\t\n| [[File:The_Dillingham_House_Main_St._Brewster,_Ma.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Brewster, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1659<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/>\n| \n|-\n|  Cpl. John Andrews-Richard Dummer House/The White Horse Inn House\t\t\n| [[File:White Horse Inn at 34 High Street in Ipswich Massachusetts USA built circa 1659.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ipswich, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1659<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/>\n| 34 High Street<ref>https://historicipswich.org/white-horse-inn-34-high-st/</ref>\n|-\n|  Philip Call House\t\t\n| [[File:Philip Call House at 26 High Street in Ipswich Massachusetts MA USA built circa 1659.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ipswich, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1659<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/>\n| 26 High Street<ref>https://historicipswich.org/philip-call-house-26-high-st/</ref>\n|-\n|  [[John Partridge House]]\t\t\n| [[File:John_Partridge_House,_Millis_MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Millis, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1659<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/>\n| \n|-\n|  Dillingham House\t\t\n|[[File:Dillingham House at Main Street in Sandwich MA Massachusetts built circa 1659.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Sandwich, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1659<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/>\n| 71 Main St<ref>Own One of the Oldest and Most Haunted Houses on Cape Cod https://fun107.com/own-one-of-the-oldest-and-most-haunted-houses-on-cape-cod-photos/ https://fun107.com/own-one-of-the-oldest-and-most-haunted-houses-on-cape-cod-photos/</ref>\n|-\n|  Wade House\t\t\n|\n| [[Scituate, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1659<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/>\n| \n|-\n| [[Parkman Tavern]]\t\n| [[File:Parkman_Tavern,_Concord_MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Concord, Massachusetts]]\n| 1659<ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/>\n|\n|-\n| [[James Blake House]]\n| [[File:James Blake House, Dorchester, Massachusetts - exterior.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]]\n| 1661\n| Oldest house in Boston (dendrochronology in 2007 determined the actual construction date [http://www.period-homes.com/Previous-Issues-07/NovemberProject07Puritan.html][dorchesterhistoricalsociety.org])\n|-\n| [[Pickering House (Salem, Massachusetts)|Pickering House]]\n| [[File:Pickering House - Salem, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1664<ref name=\"Oxford Dendrochronology\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dendrochronology.net/ma.asp|title=Oxford Dendrochronology|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| Oldest house in Salem still being lived in. It is located at 18 Broad Street in the [[Chestnut Street District]]. Dated using dendrochronology in 2007.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Pickman House]]\n| [[File:PickmanHouse Salem Massachusetts.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1664\n| Located on [[Charter Street Historic District|Charter Street]] behind the [[Peabody Essex Museum]], the oldest continually operated museum in America. The house abuts the Witch Memorial is also next to the second oldest burying ground in America.\n|-\n| [[Gedney House]]\n| [[File:Gedney House (exterior) - Salem, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1665\n| dated using dendrochronology in 2002<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Jabez Howland House]]\n| [[File:Jabez Howland House in Plymouth MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Plymouth, Massachusetts]]\n| 1667\n| Only surviving house in Plymouth where Pilgrims lived\n|-\n| [[House of the Seven Gables]]\n| [[File:House of the Seven Gables (front angle) - Salem, Massachusetts.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1668\n| [[National Historic Landmark]], setting of the [[Nathaniel Hawthorne]] novel. Dated using dendrochronology in 2005.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Swett-Ilsley House]]\n| [[File:Swett-Ilsley House - Newbury, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Newbury, Massachusetts]]\n| 1670\n|\n|-\n| [[Judge Samuel Holten House]]\n| [[File:Judge Samuel Holten House - Danvers, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Danvers, Massachusetts]]\n| 1670\n|\n|-\n| [[Chaplin-Clarke House]]\n| [[File:Chaplin-Clarke House, December 2016, Rowley MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Rowley, Massachusetts]]\n| 1670 c.\n| Oldest part built around 1670, leanto section added around 1700 before a change in ownership.\n|-\n|  Merchant-Choate House\t\n| [[File:Merchant-Choate House at 103 High Street in Ipswich MA Massachusetts USA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ipswich, Massachusetts]]\n| 1670/71\n| Also, known as Tuttle House (103 High Street). The House is definitely dated from 1670/71 by tree rings.<ref>https://www.dendrochronology.com/ith.html/</ref> Dendrochronology dating it from 1670s with some earlier beams and bracing, and possibly an earlier construction date.<ref>https://historicipswich.org/shatswell-house-88-90-high-street/</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Witch House]]\n| [[File:The witch house salem 2009.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1675\n| Also called the Jonathan Corwin House, this was the home of Judge [[Jonathan Corwin]]  [https://web.archive.org/web/20120413093247/http://mass.historicbuildingsct.com/?p=103] and is the only structure still standing in [[Salem, Massachusetts]] with direct ties to the [[Salem Witch Trials]] of 1692.[http://www.salemweb.com/witchhouse/] The house is now a museum operated by the City of Salem, and is open seasonally.\n|-\n| [[Hoxie House]]\n| [[File:Hoxie House in Sandwich MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Sandwich, Massachusetts]]\n| 1675 c.\n| One of the oldest houses on [[Cape Cod]].\n|-\n| [[Salem Maritime National Historic Site#Narbonne House|Narbonne House]]\n| [[File:Narbonne House - Salem, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1675\n| The house is on the waterfront in Salem at the [[Salem Maritime National Historic Site]] and owned by the [[National Park Service]].  The site has 12 historic structures, including the Customs House, and a replica of the sailing ship ''[[Friendship of Salem]]''. Dated using dendrochronology in 2002.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Deane Winthrop House]]\n| [[File:Deane Winthrop House Winthrop MA 02.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Winthrop, Massachusetts]]\n| 1675\n| Dated by dendrochronology to 1675,<ref name=\"Oxford Dendrochronology\"/> with an addition of 1695. Currently it is owned by the Winthrop Improvement and Historical Association. This building is one of the oldest wood frame houses in the country and it is the oldest continuously lived-in home. Located at 40 Shirley Street, the Deane Winthrop House is a registered National Historic Site.\n|-\n| [[Auld Lang Syne (house)]] \n| [[File:Auld_Lang_Syne_Sconset_(NBY_23767).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Nantucket, Massachusetts]]\n| 1675\n| possibly the oldest house on Nantucket, and a former fisherman's cottage in [[Sconset]]\n|-\n| Capen House\n| \n| [[Milton, Massachusetts]]\n| 1675\n| Dating using dendrochronology in 2002.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[John Whipple House]]\n| [[File:John Whipple House, 53 South Main Street, Ipswich (Essex County, Massachusetts).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ipswich, Massachusetts]]\n| 1677\n| [[National Historic Landmark]]. Dating using dendrochronology in 2002.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Peter Tufts House]]\n| [[Image:Peter Tufts House, Medford, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Medford, Massachusetts]]\n| 1677\u20138 c.\n| The oldest brick house in Massachusetts.<ref>Coolidge, Ruth Dame. ''Round About Old Medford'', Medford Historical Society, 1934.</ref><ref>Hooper, John H. \"Some Old Medford Houses and Estates\" ''Medford Historic Register''. VII:3 (July 1904).</ref>\n|-\n| [[Coffin House]]\n| [[File:Coffinhouse2007.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Newbury, Massachusetts]]\n| 1678\n| One of the oldest extant examples of the principal [[rafter]]/common [[purlin]] roof. Dated using dendrochronology in 2002.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[John Balch House]]\n| [[File:John Balch House - Beverly, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Beverly, Massachusetts]]\n| 1680\n| dated using dendrochronology in 2006<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Paul Revere House]]\n| [[File:Paul Revere House side view.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| 1680 c.\n| Oldest building in downtown Boston.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paulreverehouse.org/about/paulreverehouse.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-06-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080715114049/http://www.paulreverehouse.org/about/paulreverehouse.shtml |archivedate=2008-07-15 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Hart House\n| [[File:Hart House Tavern 51 Linebrook Road Ipswich, Massachusetts MA USA built circa 1680 or earlier.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ipswich, Massachusetts]]\n| 1680 \n| Now a tavern. It is located at 51 Linebrook Road and was dated using dendrochronology in 2006<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/> One room is at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref>https://www.metmuseum.org/about-the-met/curatorial-departments/the-american-wing/hart-room</ref>\n|-\n| [[Old Ship Church]]\n| [[Image:OldShipChurchView.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Hingham, Massachusetts]]\n| 1681\n| Oldest church building in Massachusetts; only remaining [[Puritan]] 17th century [[Meeting house|meetinghouse]] in America; oldest church in continuous [[Ecclesiology|ecclesiastical]] use in America.\n|-\n| [[Saugus Iron Works National Historic Site|Ironmaster's House]]\n| [[File:Saugus Iron Works - house.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Saugus, Massachusetts]]\n| 1681\n| Also known as the Appleton House.  This was part of the [[Saugus Iron Works]], which was a major industrial complex.  It has been restored and is open to the public.\n|-\n| [[Cooper-Frost-Austin House]]\n| [[File:Cooper-Frost-Austin House, Cambridge, Massachusetts - front.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n| 1681\n| Oldest house in Cambridge, verified using dendrochronology in 2002.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Parson Capen House]]\n| [[File:Parson Capen House - Topsfield, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Topsfield, Massachusetts]]\n| 1683\n| Oldest house in Topsfield.\n|-\n| [[Pierce House (Dorchester, Massachusetts)]]\n| [[File:Pierce House Boston MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]]\n| 1683\n| One of the oldest houses in Boston. Dated using dendrochronology in 2002.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| 20 White Place\n| \n| [[Brookline, Massachusetts]]\n| 1683\n| Dated using dendrochronology in 2007.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[John Ward House (Salem, Massachusetts)|John Ward House]]\n| [[File:John Ward House.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1684\n| This house is a [[National Historic Landmark]] at 132 Essex Street in [[Salem, Massachusetts]] in the [[Downtown Salem District]]; it was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1968.\n|-\n| [[Quincy Homestead]]\n| [[File:Quincy Homestead Quincy MA 01.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n| 1686\n| Home to four generations of Quincys, including Dorothy Quincy Hancock. Maintained by Commonwealth of Massachusetts Department of Conservation and Recreation as well as the National Society of Colonial Dames in America in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.\n|-\n| [[Jethro Coffin House]]\n| [[File:Jethro Coffin House, Sunset Hill, Nantucket (Nantucket County, Massachusetts).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Nantucket, Massachusetts]]\n| 1686\n| Oldest house on Nantucket Island.\n|-\n| [[William Murray House]]\n| [[File:William Murray House.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| 1688\n| A historic house at 39 Essex Street\n|-\n| [[Claflin-Richards House]]\n| [[File:Claflin-Richards House - Wenham, MA - front view.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Wenham, Massachusetts]]\n| 1690 \n|Constructed with [[ogee]] braces, an architectural hallmark of 16th- and 17th-century English dwellings. \n|-\n| [[Spencer-Peirce-Little Farm]]\n| [[File:Spencer-Peirce-Little Farm (front) - Newbury, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Newbury, Massachusetts]]\n| 1690 or earlier\n| One of the oldest stone buildings in New England.\n|-\n| [[Old Jail (Barnstable, Massachusetts)|Old Jail]]\n| [[File:Oldest wooden jail in America.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Barnstable, Massachusetts]]\n| 1690\n| Oldest wooden prison in America.\n|-\n| [[Boardman House (Saugus, Massachusetts)|Boardman House]]\n| [[File:Boardman House - Saugus MA - general view.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Saugus, Massachusetts]]\n| 1692<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historicnewengland.org/historic-properties/homes/boardman-house|title=Boardman House|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| Formerly known as the Scotch Boardman House. Also known as the Bennet-Boardman House.\n|-\n| [[Kimball Tavern]]\n| [[File:Kimball Tavern Antiques, Bradford MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Haverhill, Massachusetts]]\n| 1692\n| The [[Kimball Tavern]] is among the oldest buildings in Massachusetts, and one of the oldest buildings in the city of [[Haverhill, Massachusetts|Haverhill]]. A plaque identifies it as the site of the founding of [[Bradford College (United States)|Bradford College]] in 1802.\n|-\n| [[Stanley Lake House]]\n| [[File:Stanley Lake House, Topsfield MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Topsfield, Massachusetts]]\n| 1693\n| Stanley Lake House, built in 1693, is a historic house at 95 River Road in Topsfield, Massachusetts. It was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1990.\n|-\n| [[Browne House]]\n| [[File:Browne House - Watertown, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Watertown, Massachusetts]]\n| 1694\n| Oldest house in Watertown.\n|-\n| [[Parker Tavern]]\n| [[File:Parker Tavern Reading MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Reading, Massachusetts]]\n| 1694\n| Believed to have been built in 1694 by Abraham Bryant. Operated as a tavern during the Revolution by Ephraim Parker. The building was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1975. No dendrochronology.\n|-\n| [[Dickinson-Pillsbury-Witham House]]\n| [[File:Dickinson-Pillsbury-Witham_House_092118.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Georgetown, Massachusetts]]\n| 1700 c.\n| The Dickinson-Pillsbury-Witham House was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1990.\n|-\n| [[Hart House (Lynnfield, Massachusetts)|Hart House]]\n| [[File:Hart House, Lynnfield MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Lynnfield, Massachusetts]]\n| 1695 c.\n|\n|-\n| [[Isaac Goodale House]]\n| [[File:IpswichMA IsaacGoodaleHouse.jpg|100px]]\n| Built in [[Salem, Massachusetts]]; moved to [[Ipswich, Massachusetts]] in 1928.\n|1695 c.\n| Date from architectural survey, available on Massachusetts Cultural Resource Information System website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=IPS.633|title=MACRIS|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Manning Manse]]\n| [[File:BillericaMA ManningManse.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Billerica, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1696\n|\n|-\n|  Deacon Wrestling Brewster House\t\n| [[File:Deacon Wrestling Brewster House, Kingston, MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Kingston, Massachusetts]]\n| 1696 c.\n| Located at 18 Brewster Brewster Road. It is believed that the house dates to c. 1696 to 1700.<ref>Massachusetts Historical Commission  http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=KIN.313</ref><ref name=\"firstperiodnewengland.wordpress.com\"/> No dendrochronology survey.\n|-\n| [[Dwight-Derby House]]\n| [[File:Dwight-Derby House Medfield.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Medfield, Massachusetts]]\n| 1697\n| dated using dendrochronology in 2007.<ref name=\"oxford-dendrolab.com\"/>\n|-\n| [[Isaac Winslow House]]\n| [[File:Isaac Winslow House, Marshfield MA.jpg|100px]]\n| Marshfield, Massachusetts\n| 1699\n| Residence of a governor of the Plymouth Colony; now a museum.\n|-\n| [[Solomon Kimball House (Wenham, Massachusetts)|Solomon Kimball House]]\n| [[File:Solomon Kimball House, Wenham MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Wenham, Massachusetts]]\n| c. 1700<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=WNH.121|title=MACRIS Details|website=mhc-macris.net|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref>\n| Although the house is named for its nineteenth- and early twentieth-century owner Solomon Kimball, it was built by Thomas and Mary (Solart) Kilham (or Killam). The date of construction is based on a March 6, 1695/6 timber grant to Thomas Kilham by the town of Wenham, of enough pine timber to yield 700 boards.<ref>Wenham Historical Society, ''Wenham Town Records, 1642\u20131706'' (Salem, Massachusetts: Newcomb & Gauss, 1930), 1:130.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Hatch Homestead and Mill Historic District|Hatch Homestead]]\n| [[File:Hatch House in Marshfield MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marshfield, Massachusetts]]\n| 1700 ca.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=MRS.203|title=MACRIS Details|website=mhc-macris.net|access-date=2018-01-10}}</ref>\n| Purportedly the oldest continuously occupied house in Massachusetts.\n|-\n| [[John Alden House]]\n| [[File:John Alden House in Duxbury, Massachusetts.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Duxbury, Massachusetts]]\n| ca. 1700\n| A National Historic Landmark, dating to ca. 1700 .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nhl/find/statelists/ma/JohnandPriscillaAldenFamilySites.pdf|title=National Historic Landmark Nomination, page 4|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Rebecca Nurse Homestead]]\n| [[File:RebeccaNurseHouse2006.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Danvers, Massachusetts]]\n| ca. 1700\n| This house was built around ca. 1700.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Framed Houses of Massachusetts Bay 1625-1725|last=Cummings|first=Abbott|publisher=Belknap|year=1979|isbn=|location=|pages=123}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[John Humphreys House]]\n| [[File:Sir John Humphreys House.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Swampscott, Massachusetts]]\n|1700 c.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=SWA.71|title=MACRIS|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| [[Old Powder House]]\n| [[File:Old Powder House (Somerville, Massachusetts) - DSC04316.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Somerville, Massachusetts]]\n| 1704\n| Oldest stone building in Massachusetts\n|-\n| [[Capt. Timothy Johnson House]]\n| [[File:NorthAndoverMA CaptTimothyJohnsonHouse.jpg|100px]]\n| [[North Andover, Massachusetts]]\n| 1720\n| First Period Colonial home\n|-\n| [[Peak House (Medfield, Massachusetts)|Peak House]]\n| [[File:Peak House, Medfield MA.jpg|Peak House, Medfield MA|alt=Peak House, Medfield MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Medfield, Massachusetts]]\n| 1711\n| The Peak House is a first period cottage featuring peak style architecture and post-and-beam construction. It is the only freestanding structure of its kind and one of the earliest surviving examples of Post-medieval (Elizabethan) architecture in the United States.<ref>http://medfieldhistoricalsociety.org/historic-medfield/peak-house/</ref> First built in 1668, the original structure burned during [[King Philip's War]] in 1676 and was later reconstructed.<ref>https://patch.com/massachusetts/medfield/uniquely-medfield-east-main-street-the-gateway-into-medfield</ref>\n|-\n| [[St. Michael's Church (Marblehead, Massachusetts)]]\n| [[File:St. Michael's Church in Marblehead Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Marblehead, Massachusetts]]\n| 1714\n| Oldest Episcopal parish church building on its original site in New England.\n|-\n| [[Samuel Chase House]]\n| [[File:Samuel Chase House, West Newbury MA.jpg|100px]]\n| [[West Newbury, Massachusetts]]\n| ca. 1715\n| One of the few brick houses of the period.\n|-\n| [[Boston Light]]\n| [[File:Boston Light.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Boston]]\n| 1716 / 1783\n| First lighthouse established in the US, 1716. The current tower, built in 1783, is the second oldest existing lighthouse in the USA (after [[Sandy Hook Light]], New Jersey).\n|-\n| [[John Adams Birthplace]]\n| [[File:John Adams birthplace, Quincy, Massachusetts.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n| 1722<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dendrochronology.com/jab.html|title=Oxford Tree-Ring Laboratory|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| Oldest existing building within which a future [[President of the United States]] was born ([[John Adams]], October 30, 1735)\n<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/adam/learn/historyculture/places.htm National Park Service description of the John Adams Birthplace, as part of the Adams National Historic Park in Quincy, MA.]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bellingham-Cary House]]\n|[[File:Bellingham-Cary House Chelsea MA.jpg|100px]]\n|[[Chelsea, Massachusetts]]\n|1724<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dendrochronology.com/bch.html|title=Oxford Dendrochronology Lab}}</ref>\n|The '''Bellingham-Cary House''' is a [[historic house museum]] at 34 Parker Street in [[Chelsea, Massachusetts]].  It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1974.\n|-\n| [[Josiah Day House]]\n| [[File:Josiah Day House.jpg|100px]]\n| [[West Springfield, Massachusetts|West Springfield]]\n| 1754\n| Oldest known [[brick]] [[salt-box]] style home in the United States.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of historic houses in Massachusetts]]\n*[[Oldest buildings in the United States]]\n*[https://historicipswich.org/first-period-houses/ First Period houses in Ipswich, Massachusetts]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oldest buildings in Massachusetts}}\n[[Category:Lists of oldest buildings and structures in the United States|Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Architecture in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Massachusetts|Buildings oldest]]\n[[Category:Colonial architecture in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts history-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Old houses", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed date of construction with citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_the_oldest_buildings_in_Massachusetts"}
